column33: Extrachromosomal circular DNA (eccDNA) characterization in bone cells
column43: Extrachromosomal circular DNA (eccDNA) is circular DNA of chromosomal origin that is commonly found in somatic cells, in both cancerous and noncancerous conditions. However, their biosynthesis and functions remain highly debated. In tumors, eccDNA can act as biomarkers for cancer diagnosis and can amplify oncogenes to drive tumorigenesis and drug resistance, but their purpose in noncancerous cells is largely undetermined. Purifying and sequencing eccDNA is thus a critical prerequisite in order to better understand their biogenesis, function, and impact on phenotype. This study specifically examines eccDNA in noncancerous bone cells using the MLO-Y4, MLO-A5, UAMS32, and ST2 cell lines. We first isolate total DNA from the cells before employing the developed eccDNA enrichment method using exonuclease V for initial linear DNA removal, then restriction enzyme cutting for extraneous circular mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) removal. We subsequently perform rolling circle amplification, sequencing using Oxford Nanopore MinION flow cell, and analysis using the CReSIL bioinformatics tool to characterize the eccDNA for comparison across the different bone cell lines. The latter portion of this study shifts to an in vivo examination of eccDNA using mouse bone. The overarching goal of this project is to provide a novel investigation of eccDNA in noncancerous bone cells and to further promote the discussion of its potential applications and functions.

column33: ATF6 and EZH2 balance MHC-I presentation and immunotherapy effectiveness in metastatic melanoma
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Clinical outcomes for metastatic melanoma have significantly improved since the introduction of immune checkpoint inhibitors (ICIs), which function to prevent deactivation and increase the anti-tumor activity of a patient's T-cells. Although ICIs have revolutionized the management of metastatic melanoma, only 50% of patients exhibit immunotherapy responsiveness. Therefore, identifying the hallmarks of ICI responsiveness is needed to advance and improve clinical outcomes. Major histocompatibility complex class I (MHC-I) is an antigen presentation protein critical to the immune surveillance and recognition of cancer cells. Resistance to ICI therapy is correlated with downregulated MHC-I antigen presentation genes, decreased T-cell mediated killings, and increased oxidative metabolism. To investigate the mechanisms behind the pathways of responsiveness, B16-F10 mouse melanoma cell lines were cultured under conditions of prolonged metabolic stress. Removing glucose from the media forces melanoma cells to adapt to galactose supplementation, increasing levels of oxidative metabolism, and replicating the metabolic stress and harsh conditions of a tumor microenvironment. Proteomic analysis confirmed that the metabolically adapted cells successfully recreate the ICI responder phenotype. In addition, activating transcription factor 6 (ATF6) was found to increase in the galactose-adapted cells. ATF6 is a sensor of endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress that initiates the unfolded protein response, which combats ER stress in highly burdened cells. Histone modifying enzymes were also found to be dysregulated, specifically EZH2, a histone methyltransferase that is involved in regulation of MHC-I antigen presentation. To investigate the regulation of MHC-I and ICI response, ATF6 and EZH2 mutant cell lines were established and combined with activated CD8+ T-cells to provide insight into the mechanisms of tumor killing  under conditions of high ER stress and/or transcriptional regulation

column33: Development of specialty histological staining methods for zebrafish
column43: Danio rerio (zebrafish) have become a useful animal research model having a high similarity to humans with regards to their histological makeup. Standard protocols relating to the care and use of zebrafish were compiled and adapted for implementation for Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee review of the Ouachita Baptist University animal facility. These protocols include all facets of daily maintenance and care of the animals through euthanizing, emergency procedures, lab personnel training, and website development for public feedback regarding animal welfare.  An additional part of this project was the optimizing and adaptation of histology protocols for zebrafish necropsy, tissue preparation and staining procedures for standard Hematoxylin and Eosin (H&E) staining as well as Masson’s trichrome staining.  These procedures will be used to yield histological samples during undergraduate coursework in histology in the fall semester as well as support future research.  The specific staining procedures, which use detailed protocols adapted from current best practices, will be used to visualize and distinguish various tissue types for examination and comparison in future research. Furthermore, zebrafish breeding protocols were optimized for studies concerning sex determination of zebrafish in the early embryonic stages of development.

column33: Isolating, Characterizing, and Analyzing the Effects of Bacteriophages Sourced from Beef Products, Wastewater, and Spinach against Colibactin-Producing E. coli Strains
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: The human gut microbiome is an important location for microorganisms to provide homeostasis for biological activities in the intestines. An imbalance in the gut microbiome can lead to various gastrointestinal diseases such as irritable bowel syndrome, inflammatory bowel disease, and colorectal cancer which has been labeled as the third leading cause of cancer deaths according to the American Cancer Society. Research has shown that a common detection with these gastrointestinal diseases is an increase in E. coli population, more specifically colibactin-producing E. coli strains. Colibactin is a genotoxin that is mainly produced by E. coli and is known to target bacteria containing prophage thus triggering phage production. The objective of this study was to isolate and characterize new bacteriophages that have antimicrobial activity against colibactin-producing E. coli. Sources such as beef products, wastewater, and spinach are known to contain an E. coli population, thus becoming the sources that were chosen for this research. Twelve wastewater samples, twenty-eight beef samples, and fifteen spinach samples were screened for the presence of target bacteriophages. Attacking the host cells using bacteriophages through spot-on-lawn assays has been the methodology used to inspect two colibactin-producing E. coli strains (NC101, SP15) and one quality control strain, E. coli ATCC 25922 in this project. Currently, one beef sample and 12 wastewater samples mixed with a combination of E. coli strains against different host cells were tested to contain bacteriophages. This project aims to isolate the DNA from these bacteriophages and characterize the genome through genomic sequencing.

column33: Olanzapine Inhibits Metabolism of 5F-APINACA
column43: Synthetic cannabinoids are a persistent substance of abuse in the United States and account for approximately one third of new psychoactive substances produced in 2019. Synthetic cannabinoids mimic the “high” from cannabis, and yet they pose significant health risks such as psychosis, seizures, hallucinations, and death. While this issue alone is worrisome, the problem becomes even more pronounced when synthetic cannabinoids are taken with other drugs. Evidence of drug mixtures are shown by combinations found in clinical and pathology reports. Those combinations can cause drug-drug interactions between them leading to unexpected, elevated doses that increase adverse effects. Sadly, despite its likely common occurrence, there exists little reliable data in place that can accurately predict the significance of drug-drug interactions for synthetic cannabinoids. Drug combinations are more probable for those with mental health disorders, who are also prone to substance use disorders. Drug-drug interactions then result when those drugs compete for the same metabolizing enzymes. Consequently, we hypothesize that the antipsychotic olanzapine will inhibit metabolism of the synthetic cannabinoid 5F-APINACA. Both drugs have been found in combination in drug abusers and they undergo metabolism by the same CYP3A4 enzyme. We are testing this hypothesis by carrying out metabolic reactions using human liver microsomes and analyzing them by HPLC. Preliminary studies have shown that when Olanzapine is added to 5F-APINACA, enzymatic activity decreases and substrate binding affinity decreases.  Once complete, these studies will provide valuable data that will serve as a foundation to conduct more advanced studies over the topic of drug-drug interaction.

column33: Scoping Review of Telehealth Definitions
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Introduction: The use of telehealth in the U.S. has rapidly grown in recent years. Given this recent growth, the need to define telehealth has become important for various audiences (e.g., practitioners, policymakers, insurers). This scoping review examines the current use of definitions related to telehealth.
Methods: A scoping review was conducted to answer three key research questions regarding telehealth-related definitions: 1) What issues and challenges exist with current telehealth definitions, especially the terms “telehealth” and “telemedicine” in the U.S.? 2) What are the current telehealth definitions used among U.S. stakeholders and across the healthcare literature? 3) What are key considerations when selecting telehealth definitions that are the right fit for services or programs provided? 
Results: Differences exist in how the academic literature, organizations, and legislation use the terms “telehealth” and “telemedicine,” either interchangeably or as distinct terms (60% of academic literature, 76% of organizations, and no legislative documents defined them as distinct terms). Eighty percent of the scoped entities provided a specific definition for telehealth. Similarly, 80% percent of the entities had a telemedicine definition, out of which 50% of them represented telemedicine as having a clinical care focus, while the other half included activities other than clinical care, such as continuing medical education or administrative processes. 
Conclusions: Existing telehealth definitions vary considerably across sources due to differences in intended audience and purpose. Overall, clarity and communication will be improved by using the more-encompassing term “telehealth” over the term “telemedicine” and including three key components within telehealth definitions: 1) Service (what is being delivered?), 2) Structure (how is it being delivered?), and 3) Purpose (why is it being delivered?).

column33: The Plausible Role of Histone H2A Proteins in Bdelloid Rotifer DNA Repair
column43: Multiple DNA double-strand breaks caused by desiccation are lethal to most eukaryotes. Bdelloid rotifers, however, are an exception. These microscopic, aquatic animals possess unique DNA repair capabilities that allow them to survive desiccation. Their DNA repair mechanism is unusually efficient and not yet understood. In other eukaryotes, chromatin - specifically histone proteins - plays a key role in DNA repair. Bdelloids have seven histone H2A proteins with longer C-terminal tails than in other animals, so these proteins are good candidates for having a role in DNA repair. The objective of this project is to determine which bdelloid histone H2A proteins are likely involved in DNA repair. First, to identify polyadenylated histone mRNAs, 3’ random amplification of cDNA ends (3’ RACE) was used to sequence 3’ UTRs of histone genes in the bdelloid Adineta vaga. Transcripts with poly-A tails likely represent histone variants that might regulate DNA repair. Next, the function of histone H2A proteins H2Abd and H2Abd1 in A. vaga were investigated by using CRISPR genome editing to inactivate the genes. Single-guide RNAs (sgRNAs) designed to excise each gene were first tested using an in vitro Cas9 cleavage assay. A DNA template was also designed to replace each histone gene with the GFP gene during homology-directed repair. CRISPR was carried out by electroporating rotifer embryos with the sgRNA/Cas9 complexes and the GFP repair template. Fluorescence microscopy was used to find evidence of genome editing via GFP expression in rotifers. Once a histone mutant is identified, CRISPR will be used to inactivate histone H2A genes that are potentially involved in DNA repair. Mutant rotifers will be desiccated to cause DNA damage, then rehydrated to induce DNA repair. Ultimately, a reduced recovery rate in mutant rotifers relative to wild type rotifers would suggest that the targeted histone H2A gene has an important role in DNA repair.

column33: Synthesis of Pyridine-fused Benzothiophene To Generate a Library of Novel Bioactive Compounds
column43:
Benzothiophene is a highly valuable starting material that is utilized in various industries including pigments and pharmaceutical drugs, for the synthesis of more complex molecules. The medicinal interest in its derivatives has surged due to its remarkable antibacterial properties and therapeutic potential against a wide range of diseases. These derivatives exhibit a diverse array of beneficial characteristics such as anticancer, anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, antitubercular, antidiabetic, and anticonvulsant activities. Consequently, they serve as crucial building blocks for the development of novel pharmaceuticals. 
The primary focus of this presentation is on synthesis of a series of novel fused heterocycles containing benzothiophene and pyridine to test them against different bacterial strains. The synthesis of benzothiophene involves a reaction between 2,5-dihydroxy-¬¬1,4-dithiane and 2-fluorobenzonitrile derivatives, resulting in the formation of a benzene-fused thiophene ring.  This aminoaldehyde was further reacted with 1,3-diketones to synthesize a library of compounds.
Tests are currently ongoing to see the potential antibacterial properties of the novel compounds.

column33: Analysis of Cancer Cell Survival using AI Confluence Analysis
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Clonogenic cell survival assays have long since been used in tumor and cell biology to analyze the effect of chemotherapy and radiotherapy on proliferating cancer cells. Clonogenic assays utilize the reproductive capabilities of single cells to form colonies. After a period of growth (10-14 days), these colonies are fixed, stained and then can be counted and the surviving fraction of colonies can be used to generate survival curves that provide an endpoint analysis of the effect of the treatment on cell proliferation. growth and the ability of chemo and radiotherapies to combat tumor growth. Traditionally, Clonogenic Assays utilize 6-well cell culture plates for cell seeding and staining, which limits the ability to examine the effects of multiple drug concentrations on different cancer cell lines without the use of a large amount of materials and time investment. An alternative approach to traditional clonogenics using 96-well cell culture plates and confluence analysis would allow a high-throughput analysis of the effects of multiple drug concentrations on cancer cell lines. If the cell survival data obtained from AI confluence analysis and traditional clonogenics are related, the Wolfe lab would effectively be able to replace traditional clonogenic assays with a more efficient, high-throughput method of examining cancer cell survival in various drug and radiation conditions.

column33: Role of platelet glycoprotein Ibα in radiation-induced cytogenetic damage
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: In a large-scale nuclear event, individuals may be exposed to high levels of irradiation, which can have detrimental effects on the cytogenetic makeup of bone marrow, stem, and progenitor cells responsible for generating various blood cell types, including platelets. Platelets play a crucial role in communication with hematopoietic cells and carry numerous proteins and biologically active compounds. This study aims to investigate the potential impact of platelet glycoprotein Ibα (GPIbα) in modifying radiation-induced cytogenetic damage. Female mice, including wild-type and hIL-4R/Ibα mice, were exposed to a total body irradiation dose of 8Gy. Bone marrow cells were collected eight days after exposure for conventional and molecular cytogenetic analysis. The types and total number of chromosomal aberrations between hIL-4R/Ibα mice and age-matched wild-type mice were compared following irradiation. Data findings suggest that platelets play a role in modifying radiation-induced chromosomal damage. Preliminary data show that mice with dysfunctional GPIbα (hIL-4R/Ibα mice) exhibit increased inflammation, which is one of the major contributors of cytogenetic damage.

column33: Investigating HELB activity in response to phosphorylation of serine 1048
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: The helicase family contains numerous enzymes that are vital to processes involving DNA or RNA unwinding. DNA Helicase B (HELB) is one such enzyme that plays an essential role in maintaining genomic integrity. Although HELB is known to be crucial for genomic maintenance, preliminary data identified several sites of phosphorylation on the protein that reduce its enzymatic activity when phosphorylated. However, the effects of phosphorylating individual residues are unknown. In order to investigate the effects of phosphorylation on serine 1048 (S1048) of HELB, we created a plasmid with a serine to aspartic acid mutation (S1048D) to mimic the effects of phosphorylation. We have developed a protocol to express and purify HELB from E. coli, and DNA unwinding assays with the purified wild type HELB confirmed that active enzyme was produced. We are currently purifying the S1048D HELB variant whose activity we will compare to the activity of wild type HELB in order to discover how phosphorylation of this specific site affects HELB activity in vitro. Preliminary data suggests that the phosphorylation of HELB at six residues, including S1048, decreases its activity, and that the S1048 residue is one of the most phosphorylated sites in human HELB. Thus, we expect reduced DNA unwinding assay of the purified S1048D HELB variant relative to the wild type HELB. Discovering the activity of this HELB variant and others will provide valuable information that can be used to predict the effect of HELB phosphorylation on its activities within the cell.

column33: Photocatalysis on Metal Oxide Structures to Purify and Disinfect Water for Space Travel
column43: Photocatalysis has received significant interest as an alternative method for microbial disinfection in water. Photocatalyst materials absorb light, produce electron–hole pairs, and generate reactive oxygen species (ROS), which cause damage to the cell walls and breaks down cellular materials of bacteria. A photocatalytic water disinfection method is an environmentally friendly approach and more effective compared to traditional methods such as chlorination, ozonation and direct UV – light disinfection.  However, most of the ZnO nanostructure synthesis methods use toxic chemicals, are expensive, complicated, and non-scalable. Besides that, ZnO photocatalysts are often synthesized in powder form, which are suspended in water. Although suspended nanostructures have high surface area, their recovery and reuse are challenging, and may cause secondary pollution. Hence, there is a need for synthesizing robust nanostructured photocatalysts that are immobilized on supports, in a scalable, cost – effective and environmentally friendly way, for water disinfection applications. Here we introduce a simple and chemical- free nanostructure synthesis method using a hot water treatment (HWT) to produce immobilized metal oxide nanostructures.  In this work, we immersed Zn plates in DI water at 75C for different time durations, which resulted in the formation of ZnO nanostructures of different lengths and diameters. Morphology and crystal structure of the ZnO nanostructures were characterized using scanning electron microscopy and X–ray diffraction. We then tested the antimicrobial efficacy of these novel nanostructured surfaces and coupled this surface treatment with UV radiation. It was found that the nanostructured ZnO plates had a statistically significant antimicrobial effect, and increased kill when coupled with UV radiation. This is believed to be due to the increased formation of ROS due to the photocatalytic ZnO nanostructures.

column33: Validating proteomic findings in methionine-restricted colorectal tumors
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Colorectal cancer is the fourth leading cause of death amongst cancer patients. This is true for both men and women, in the United States and for the state of Arkansas as well. Nearly half of colorectal cancer cases are associated with a mutation in the oncogene KRAS. Both chemotherapy and radiation therapy can be used, but patients with the KRAS-mutated (KRASmut) cancer cells do not usually respond well to the treatment. These activated-KRAS mutations make it difficult for any treatment to work properly, as the tumor cells display a high resistance. From previous research in our lab, existing literatures, and with the help of proteomics data collected here at UAMS, it is evident that KRAS mutated cancer cells are highly dependent on methionine, which is an essential amino acid. We also know that KRAS contributes to the metabolic pathway NRF2 and the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway. Our hypothesis is that reducing the intake of methionine would re-sensitize the KRAS mutant cells, and hence forth making them more susceptible to treatment. Therefore, the goal of our project is to confirm that the KRAS pathway is increased in the tumors from mice that were fed a diet low in methionine, while also looking at related proteins, and comparing them to the results from growing the same cancer cells in the lab in vitro.

column33: Utilizing CRISPR/Cas9 to Investigate Putative Meiotic Recombination Hotspots in Schizosaccharomyces pombe
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: High rates of homologous recombination during meiosis are required for the faithful segregation of chromosomes and to generate genetic diversity upon which natural selection acts. Meiotic recombination is clustered at “hotspots” that are irregularly distributed across the genome. To further elucidate how discrete DNA sequences direct hotspots, we are using the CRISPR gene-editing system to introduce specific sequences into the model organism Schizosaccharomyces pombe.  We have incorporated two previously identified DNA motifs, called HES92 and HES95, that are potential hotspots into the reporter gene ade6. To accomplish this, we transformed wild-type fission yeast with a plasmid that expresses both the Cas9 endonuclease and a guide RNA that directs it to the desired region of ade6. The plasmid was co-transformed with a short DNA fragment containing the motif of interest flanked by sequences homologous to the target region. Transformants were selected by resistance to the drug G418, as well as screened for red colony color, indicating the successful introduction of mutations to ade6.  The resulting ade6 gene of selected transformants was analyzed by Sanger sequencing.  Out of four candidates sequenced so far, we have confirmed that three contain the intended mutations. Our next goal is to use these newly constructed strains in recombination tests to determine whether the inserted motifs elevate recombination levels.

column33: Male offspring of undernourished dams are protected from high fat diet-induced weight gain and display sex-specific metabolic changes
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Leptin is a hormone secreted by adipose tissue that regulates appetite largely by signaling to neurons in the hypothalamus. During neonatal development in both rodents and humans, a surge in leptin occurs and is responsible for the proper development of these hypothalamic neurons. However, leptin may also be involved in pituitary development and maturation. Studies have found that maternal undernutrition alters the leptin surge, which may cause metabolic dysfunction and weight gain in adult progeny. Musashi (MSI) is a translational regulator found in the anterior pituitary that inhibits POU1F1, a protein necessary for pituitary cell differentiation and maturation. Previous work in our lab has shown that leptin stimulates pituitary Musashi expression. This study focused on blunting the neonatal leptin surge in FVB mice with a 30% maternal caloric restriction (CR30). We hypothesized that this would alter the expression of MSI targets in neonates, and that these changes would persist in the adult offspring. Adult progenies were fed either a control diet (CTRL) or a 60% high fat diet (HFD) for 25 weeks. Surprisingly, CR30-HFD males had reduced weight (starting at 5 wks, 3.761g less than CTRL-HFD, p<0.05) compared to controls, whereas CR30-HFD females gained more weight than CTRL-HFD as originally expected. Glucose tolerance tests revealed reduced insulin resistance in CR30-HFD males, whereas CR30-HFD females were insulin resistant. CLAMS-Oxymax metabolic cage data revealed that CR30-HFD males had reduced food intake (p<0.0001), reduced energy expenditure (p<0.0001), and reduced ambulation (p<0.0001) in the dark phase. These data suggest that an undernourished maternal environment programs appetite-suppressing mechanisms within male, but not female, offspring. Proteomic data of MSI targets from CR30 adult pituitaries will elucidate potential mechanisms.

column33: Effects of the Gut Microbiome in Relation to Bone Density with Injection of Aggressive Multiple Myeloma
column43:
The big picture of this research is to see how the gut microbiome is affected by the injection of aggressive multiple myeloma. The treatments used are Sigma Anti-Bonding Calcium Carbonate (SAC) and an herbal treatment of an equal mixture of calcium and selenium supplements. Both treatments show an increase in bone density in individuals with multiple
myeloma, but the herbal treatment shows a higher increase in bone density than the SAC treatment. The Human gut microbiota plays a heavily important role in the progression of myeloma because of the composition of bacteria in the intestines [1]. The micro-organisms in the gut are highly beneficial but under specific conditions [1]. If the microbiome differentiates from those specific conditions, this effect can cause the growth of cancer cells [1]. When the bacteria that thrive from nitrogen-recycling bacteria are increased, mortality rates increase [1]. This is because of the high urea concentrations in patients with multiple myeloma [1]. This high concentration of urea is caused by the increased NH4+ production from tumor cells that, in turn, causes secretions of urea to be decreased, which causes renal function failure [1]. The goal of
this research is to figure out why herbal medicine caused an increase in bone density and if it is related to the gut microbiome and how it is related. Studies have shown that gut microbiome could influence the refractoriness of multiple myeloma.

column33: Using Myxoma Virus to Understand the Intrinsic Immune Properties of SAMD9 Protein
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Poxviruses are useful for studying host species barrier and host immunity, due to their dependence on host machinery and ability to successfully inhibit and manipulate host pathways. Various members of the poxvirus family possess proteins that affect the mammalian protein, sterile alpha motif protein 9 (SAMD9), to establish cellular infection. Despite the diverse functions of SAMD9, its underlying molecular mechanisms are unknown. To unravel the protein’s function, we utilized a rabbit infecting poxvirus, Myxoma virus (MYXV). MYXV consists of a M062 protein that affects the SAMD9 protein found in mammalian cells. The aim of this study is to understand the mode of action of SAMD9 by exploiting the interaction between SAMD9 and MYXV M062 protein. We first generated a mutant MYXV, MAV-M062R and compared it to the wildtype Lu-M062R virus. The mutation in MAV-M062R prevents binding with the SAMD9 protein, resulting in defective viral RNA and protein expression, confirmed through reverse transcriptase, real time PCR and western blot. This defect in viral replication cycle leads to its attenuated infection. The defective viral protein expression revealed the involvement of another cellular protein, eukaryotic initiation factor 2 (eIF2α), whose phosphorylation leads to global translation shutdown in the cell. Our western blot results showed induction of phosphorylation of eIF2α during infection with the mutant virus. We then analyzed the kinase responsible for eIF2α phosphorylation. For this, we assessed the involvement of 2 kinases, PERK and PKR. Our western blot data revealed that p-eIF2α is regulated in a PKR dependent manner. To further confirm this phenotype, we will study PKR KO cells infected with WT and mutant MYXV viruses. We will use western blot to analyze the role of PKR in regulating p-eIF2α during MYXV infection. This connection will enhance our understanding of how the SAMD9 protein contributes to establishing a unique antiviral state within host cells.

column33: Knocking Out Chemotherapy Symptoms: The Role of CCR2 Inactivation in Ameliorating the Ramifications Associated with Breast Cancer TAC Chemotherapy Regimen
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Introduction: As triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) emerged as a significant health concern, improvements in screening and treatment have facilitated a 90% 5-year survival rate. Despite these advances, cognitive impairment induced by chemotherapy, specifically docetaxel, doxorubicin, and cyclophosphamide (TAC) treatment, is demonstrated in many TNBC patients, manifesting as neuroinflammation, depression, and anxiety. This study evaluates the potential role of CCR2 deletion in mitigating TAC-induced anxiety and cognitive dysfunction.
Methods: Female wildtype (WT) and CCR2-KO mice were administered TAC treatment for 8 weeks, while the control groups received saline. Thirty days post-treatment, the Elevated Plus (EP) and Morris Water Maze (MWM) tests were conducted to assess anxiety-like behavior and spatial memory. To investigate the relationship between CCR2 inactivation and cognitive deficits, QIAGEN and KEGG analysis were utilized to identify significant changes in the proteome correlated with inflammation. 
 Results: In the EP test, the WT TAC mice exhibited a reluctance to explore open arms, indicating chemotherapy’s role in exacerbating anxiety. Conversely, CCR2-KO mice receiving TAC demonstrated reduced anxiety-like behavior compared to the control group and both WT groups, implying that CCR2 deficiency may alleviate TAC-induced anxiety. During the MWM, it was similarly observed that TAC impaired cognitive function of WT mice, while both CCR2-knockout groups were comparatively unaffected and successfully located the target quadrant on Days 3-5. Proteomics analysis revealed that CCR2 inactivation downregulated proteins associated with oxidative stress, potentially mitigating inflammation caused by chemotherapy.
Directions: To ensure the efficacy of CCR2 deletion as a treatment for chemotherapy symptoms, it is imperative to conduct further cognitive and anxiety-like behavioral tests and address the susceptibility to infection instigated by CCR2 deficiency.

column14: IDeA Network of Biomedical Research Excellence (INBRE)
column33: Docking Studies of Potent Antibacterial Agents against FAB Proteins
column43: Bacterial resistance to antibiotics is one of the most pressing problems of this century. Misuse and overuse of antibiotics and bacterial innate ability to develop resistance have made bacterial infections recalcitrant to most of the existing antibacterial agents. In a quest to find new antibiotics, a large number of pyrazole derivatives have been synthesized and several of these derivatives are found to be potent antibacterial agents. These potent compounds are effective against methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) and vancomycin-resistant enterococci (VRE) bacteria. Lead compounds inhibited the growth of bacteria both in planktonic and biofilms context. CRISPRi studies helped to determine the mode of action of these compounds as potent Fatty Acid Biosynthesis (FAB) inhibitors.  In this research, Autodock Vina (1.5.7) and Autodock Tools were used for computational docking studies. One of the fatty acid synthesis proteins, FabK (PDB ID: 2Z6I) showed low binding energy at -10.4 kcal/mol in a docking study with one of the synthesized pyrazole derivatives. We have also found a correlation between the results of the docking study and in vitro study. The compounds which showed low binding energy in the docking study also showed lower minimum inhibitory concentration in the in vitro study against the bacterial strains. This report helped to figure out the potent activity and better selectivity of new compounds by using computational studies, which helped to save time and resources.

column33: Synergistic Anticancer Effects of Parthenolide and Gamma-tocotrienol
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Breast cancer is the most prevalent form of cancer in women worldwide and the second most prevalent in the United States. Chemotherapy and radiation therapy are major treatments for breast cancer; however, both cause severe side effects to healthy tissues that lower the patient’s quality of life. Parthenolide (PTL), a sesquiterpene lactone that occurs naturally in the plant feverfew, and gamma-tocotrienol (GT3), a vitamin E family member and a known mevalonate pathway inhibitor that has historically been implicated in cardiovascular disease treatment, have recently garnered interest as potential anticancer agents with minimal side effects. This research aimed to determine if the combined treatment of PTL and GT3 synergistically limit MCF7 breast cancer cell proliferation and elucidate its molecular mechanisms. The synergistic effect of PTL and GT3 against MCF7 breast cancer cell proliferation, clonogenic survival, and apoptosis were evaluated by MTT, colony forming ability, western blot, and flow cytometry. The results of the MTT assay from MCF7 breast cancer cells treated with GT3 (50 µM) and/or PTL (5 µM) for 24 and 48 hours demonstrated that combined treatment suppresses the proliferation rate of MCF7 cells at a greater extent than the singular treatment with either GT3 or PTL at both time points. Colony formation assay results of MCF7 breast cancer cells treated with GT3 (5 µM) and/or PTL (0.5 µM) showed that the inhibition of colony forming ability was greater in the combined treatment groups compared to the singular treatment groups. Western blot results showed increased expression of apoptotic markers, while flow cytometry exhibited a higher percentage of apoptotic cells in combined treatment group (50 M GT3 plus 5 M PTL) as compared to the singular treatment group. In conclusion, the combination of GT3 and PTL is more potent against breast cancer cells than singular treatments, indicating its promise as a new therapeutic strategy.

column33: Exploring Ruthenium Carbonyl Complexes for Potential Fuel Sources
column43: As a society, we have become dependent on the use of fossil fuels to power our everyday life. The byproduct of these fossil fuels is carbon dioxide which is continuously pushed into the atmosphere, thereby directly contributing to climate change. Electrochemically reducing CO2 into carbon monoxide through an organometallic catalyst like [Ru(bpy)2(CO)2]2+ can create a precursor for fuel sources such as methanol and formic acid. This study analyzed reactivity of the hydroxymethyl intermediate, [Ru(bpy)2(CO)(CH2OH)]+, which is proposed to form methanol. It was hypothesized that addition of acid to the complex would protonate the hydroxymethyl group to yield methanol. Instead, infrared spectroscopy and 1H NMR suggest that the hydroxymethyl group becomes an unstable CH2 group that allows acetonitrile to attach and stabilize it.

column33: The Genetic Diversity of Warea amplexifolia
column43: Warea amplexifolia is a federally and state endangered plant due to habitat loss and fragmentation that is endemic to the central ridge system of Florida. To aid in recovery of this species, we seek to study if populations of Warea amplexifolia have lost genetic diversity, if certain populations are more diverse than others, and what populations would be best for reintroduction purposes. Whole genomic DNA from Warea amplexifolia was extracted and species-specific primers of ten microsatellite loci were used to amplify and genotype 164 individuals from seven different populations. Initial results indicate that some populations have lower genetic diversity, higher selfing rates, and likely a higher extinction risk than other populations. The populations with the largest number of plants also have the most genetic diversity and thus might be useful as sources for translocation and reintroduction purposes. We will discuss the implications of our research for the management of this critically endangered plant.

column33: Elucidating the role of type I collagen mutations on respiratory function in osteogenesis imperfecta
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Osteogenesis imperfecta (OI), or “brittle bone disease”, is a genetic disorder occurring in 1/15-20,000 births and most commonly results from changes in the quantity or quality of type I collagen, which constitutes about 90% of the organic matrix in bones. Characteristics of OI include malformed and bowed bones, small stature, easily bruised skin, blue sclera (whites of eyes look blue), and heart or respiratory problems. Perinatal mortality in OI is often the result of respiratory failure. Prior research showed that defects of the skeleton, including rib cage distortions, restrict ventilation, yet not much research has shown if lung intrinsic factors exist and lead to respiratory problems. We previously showed morphological and functional changes in the lungs of OI mouse models. Specifically, OI lungs had enlarged alveolar structures perhaps due to defective alveolar septation compared to WT mouse lungs, resulting in less surface area for gas exchange. We hypothesize that defective type I collagen in lung fibroblasts, cells producing the majority of collagen, will lead to dysregulation of lung alveolar morphogenesis and alteration in mRNA expression level of genes involved in this process. Our goal is to 1) confirm the lung findings in mice with a collagen mutation expressed only in lung tissue, eliminating the possibility for skeletal defects to impact the lung and 2) to analyze cellular and molecular changes in lung of OI mice using single-cell RNA sequencing. Identification of differentially expressed mRNA/proteins may offer new therapeutic targets to improve health and quality of life for OI patients.

column33: Challenges and Solutions in Measuring Commonly Used Hepatotoxicity Biomarkers in a Liver-on-a-chip Platform
column43: Liver-on-a-chip (liver-chip) is a microphysiological system (MPS) designed to better maintain hepatic functions and viability of liver cells cultured under in vitro conditions. The activities of alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST) are clinically used biomarkers for liver injury and are therefore have been proposed hepatotoxicity biomarkers for liver MPS. In our study of acetaminophen hepatotoxicity, we used Emulate® liver-chips, which coculture primary hepatocytes (PH) with non-parenchymal cells (NPCs) consisting of sinusoidal endothelium, Kupffer, and stellate cells. We unexpectedly found that commonly used assays for ALT and AST activities did not work in liver-chips, and efforts were undertaken to address this issue. Human PH and NPCs were cultured in the top and bottom channels, respectively, of the Emulate® liver-chips. The perfusing medium, also called effluent, was collected to determine ALT and AST. Cells were lysed using 1% Triton X-100, and then the lysate was stored in cell culture incubator for 0, 24, 48, and 72 h. ALT and AST activities were measured using the method recommended by International Federation of Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine (IFCC method). In parallel, an enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) was used to determine protein levels of ALT and AST. The activities of ALT and AST of the effluent from intact cells were undetectable (i.e., < 5 U/L). In lysed cells, ATL and AST activity were 20 and 70 U/L, respectively. However, the activity of ALT, but not AST, spontaneously decreased by about 50% every 24 h, suggesting ALT activity is not suitable for measuring cell death in liver-chips. In contrast, protein levels of ALT and AST measured by ELISA were stable over time and readily detectable in the effluent of intact cells. Our findings suggest that ALT and AST protein levels, but not activity, should be used to determine cell death in Emulate liver-chips.

column7: Ouachita Baptist University
column33: The Effect of Varying Wavelengths of Light and Hypo-gravity on Dictyostelium Discoideum's Movement and Development
column43: Dictyostelium discoideum is a prevalent eukaryotic slime mold that has been utilized in many experiments because of its distinct development as an organism. Dictyostelium d.’s life cycle starts as spores which develop into amoebae, which feed on bacteria and when conditions are right, they will develop into a multicellular structure referred to as slugs. The focal point of this experiment is to observe the movement and development of the slugs in response to different wavelengths of light and the influence of gravity using a clinostat. To conduct the experiment, ten slugs were placed in the center of each lactose peptone plate and were either attached to a clinostat which rotated at 1 rpm or placed in a stationary position inside an incubator. Each plate was either treated to blue light, red light, two variations of white light, or darkness for a period of five days. Slugs on the stationary plates are expected to move towards the light vector against the influence of gravity and towards gravity in the dark. In contrast, the plates on the clinostat will  move more towards the light and those without light treatment will orient themselves more randomly. These results will give more insight into the effects of light and gravity on the slug migration of Dictyostelium d.

column33: The Effects of BW1 on the Viability of Cancer Cells of a Mouse Model
column43: In the treatment of cancer, each method should be highly efficient and as targeted as possible. In some instances, cancers like breast or lung cancer can become ineffective or resistant to chemotherapy, the primary drug used to treat most cancer variations. With the help of alternative treatment therapeutics/drugs, these types of cancer can be dealt with more easily. The aim of the current study is to determine the therapeutic potential of BW1, a synthetic protogenesis chemical, against the murine mammary carcinomas line, 4T1, and Lewis Lung Carcinoma (LLC). Growths of LLC and 4T1 were dosed with BW1, ranging from 0.05µM to 10µM, and were allowed to incubate. After three days, the viability of the cells was assessed with a WST-8 (2-(2-methoxy-4-nitrophenyl)-3-(4-nitrophenyl)-5-(2,4-disulfophenyl)-2H-tetrazolium, monosodium salt), which shows the viability of the cells, via a colorimetric indicator caused by cell proliferation, after exposure to the therapeutic. The data was then recorded on an Excel sheet, where it was then analyzed to determine the next step. The EC50, or the concentration that causes approximately 50 percent of the cancer cells to die, for 4T1, was between 1 and 2.5 µM, while for LLC it was between 0.2 and 2 µM. Based on the results of this assay, BW1 is more effectively killing lung cancer cells than breast cancer cells.

column33: Lipidomics Evaluation of the Impact of Fentanyl Treatments on Neural Cells
column43: Fentanyl is a potent opioid analgesic used for pain management in medical settings. Because it is impossible to obtain critical dose-response and time-course data on anesthetic/analgesic-induced neural damage in human infants or children, the utilization of neural stem cell models, especially cells derived from humans, might be a good tool to evaluate the vulnerability of the nervous system. Since neural cells contain a wide variety of lipid classes and lipid species, lipidomics analysis using ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC) coupled with high-resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) was conducted to investigate the impacts of different dosages of fentanyl on neural cells. The neural cells were treated with vehicle (control) or fentanyl at 1 uM, 10 uM, or 100 uM. In total, 1830 lipid species from 20 lipid classes were detected and identified. Among the detected 20 lipid classes, the total abundance of cholesterol ester and sphingosine classes significantly decreased while ceramide and hexosylceramide classes significantly increased (>2 folds increases) in the high-dose group vs. the control. This preliminary data indicated that the ceramide pathway was disturbed by fentanyl treatments, which might provide the underlying mechanisms of fentanyl-induced neurotoxicity. The findings of this study might contribute to a broader understanding of the pharmacological effects of fentanyl on neural cells and may help develop targeted interventions to reduce adverse effects.

column33: Effects of Palmitate on Intracellular Distribution of β-Amyloid within Neuro2A Cells: Liraglutide and Metformin as Possible Alzheimer’s Disease Interventions
column36: Columbia University in the City of New York
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is the most common form of senile dementia, principally characterized by irreversible cognitive decline and impaired synaptic plasticity. While exact mechanisms of neurodegeneration are to be further elucidated upon, Familial AD is largely associated with mutations occuring in the Amyloid Precursor Protein (APP), resulting in an accumulation of β-Amyloid (Aβ) senile plaque deposits in the hippocampus and basal segments of the brain. The processing and cleaving of APP is confirmedly categorized into two pathways; the Amyloidogenic pathway, facilitated by the β-secretase cleaving enzyme (BACE1), is responsible for the release of non-membrane tethered Aβ into the luminal space. Saturated fatty acids (SFA) are increased in the cerebrospinal fluid of patients with Type-2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM). The presence of intracellular Aβ peptides in neurons derived from transgenic mice propounds a possible greater involvement of intracellular Aβ in the early pathogenesis of AD in T2DM patients, rather than extracellular. This study utilizes Confocal Fluorescence Microscopy in combination with Western Blotting to determine adverse effects of SFA exposure in transfected Neuro2A cells expressing mutant APPSwe/Ind. Such effects may include translocation of the intracellular site of Aβ generation. We will identify possible remediatory effects of two anti-diabetic agents, Metformin and Liraglutide, on the distribution of Aβ within the neuronal cell body. Preliminary results of an analysis performed on images of Neuro2A cells stained with a monoclonal antibody detecting APP indicate that in the absence of SFA, APP accumulates in a trans-Golgi network-like perinuclear compartment. However, upon exposure to palmitate, APP abundance within this compartment is decreased. We seek to determine whether APP is instead increased within the ER, suggesting that in the presence of SFA, APP retention occurs, leading to greater ER stress and neuronal death if not ameliorated.

column33: Investigating the Role of WRN Helicase in Aiding Translesion Synthesis Past G-Quadruplex Structures
column36: Arkansas School for Mathematics, Sciences, and the Arts
column39: Arkansas School for Mathematics, Sciences, and the Arts
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: DNA structures extend beyond the B-form double helix, and their misplacement can lead to mutations, dysregulation, damage, and cancer. G-quadruplexes (G4) are non-canonical DNA structures impacting replication, gene expression, and post-transcriptional events. Efficient resolution and replication of G4 structures are vital to prevent mutations, DNA damage, and cancer. G4 structures arise from guanine bases forming G-tetrads or G-quartets via Hoogsteen-hydrogen bonds. Stacking G-tetrads creates G-quadruplexes (G4). Several proteins and enzymes facilitate DNA replication across G4 structures. Werner protein (WRN), a Rec-Q family helicase involved in DNA maintenance and repair, plays a key role. Werner's syndrome, characterized by rapid aging and increased cancer risk, is associated with over 60 genetic mutations resulting in dysfunctional or shortened WRN protein. Prior studies indicate that loss of functional WRN increases genetic mutation frequency in G4-capable human telomeric regions. This study investigates how WRN aids translesion DNA polymerases in unwinding G4 structures. A polymerase extension assay employed purified human polymerase kappa (PolK) on template-primer DNA substrates capable of forming G4 structures, along with non-G4 DNA substrates as controls. The assay was conducted with and without purified WRN protein, and the results were compared. Findings reveal that WRN helicase significantly enhances PolK's replication across G4 sequences compared to PolK alone. These findings enhance our understanding of the collaborative mechanisms of essential proteins in resolving G4 DNA structures and maintaining genomic stability.

column33: Assessing the Regulatory Potential of Sites of Differential Chromatin Accessibility as a Result of Chronic Early Life Stress
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Chronic pain is a significant public health problem which affects a large percentage of the US population and incurs costs due to medical treatment and lost productivity.  Early life adversity is a well-established risk factor for the development of chronic pain. Early life adversity can be modeled in animals using the neonatal limited bedding model, which alters the pattern of maternal care behaviors and provokes early life stress in the offspring. Epigenetic memory of these altered patterns of maternal touch can then be stored in the dorsal root ganglion (DRG) which innervates the skin and contains the cell nuclei for peripheral sensory neurons.  Using this model, we have identified regions of differentially accessible chromatin in the rat DRG which are associated with increased sensitivity to mechanical touch following early life stress.  We hypothesize that these regions may epigenetically prime sensory neurons to regulate sensory transduction pathways and increase an individual's susceptibility for chronic pain later in life. We tested high ranking differentially accessible regions using luciferase assays to determine their regulatory potential.  We cloned each sequence into a luciferase expressing vector and transfected this plasmid into the 50B11 rat immortalized nociceptor cell line. Approximately 48 hours after transfection, we added the luciferase substrate and measured the bioluminesce emitted from each reaction to quantitate a measure of each sequences’ regulatory capabilities.

column33: Targeting the non-catalytic function of BRK kinase using BRK-specific PROTACs
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: A kinase is a type of enzyme that transfers the gamma phosphate of ATP to a substrate to regulate various cellular processes. Kinases can be thought of as traffic signals that regulate the flow of information in a cell. Overexpression or mutation of kinases has been shown to occur in many cancers. Kinases can be inhibited using small molecules that occupy the ATP binding pocket to inhibit the process of phosphorylation. Specifically, protein tyrosine kinase 6 or PTK6 (aka BRK) is currently being investigated in cancers since it is overexpressed in breast, ovarian, and prostate cancers and aids in the proliferation, metastasis, and development of tumor cells.1 Kinase inhibitors that block catalytic activity of BRK have been unsuccessful in clinical trials for treatment of BRK-associated breast cancer suggesting a possible non-catalytic role of BRK in cancer. The non-catalytic mechanism of the kinase can be targeted using proteolysis targeting chimeras or PROTACs. These PROTACS are heterobifunctional molecules with two separate ligands, in which one ligand binds to the target protein, and the other binds to the E3 ubiquitin ligase system. The PROTAC brings the target protein and the E3 ubiquitin ligase system together, so the protein of interest can be ubiquitinated and degraded by the ubiquitin-proteasome system.2 Degrading the BRK kinase in this way may be effectively used to fight breast cancer. A PROTAC specific to BRK for its targeted degradation is currently under development. A potent inhibitor of the kinase has already been developed by our laboratory, which will serve as a ligand to bind to the BRK kinase. Now, a second ligand i.e., E3 ligand must be added to the molecule, to mark the kinase for degradation. The synthesized PROTACs will be investigated for proteolytic degradation of BRK.

column33: Developing a novel, biomimetic, poly(δ-valerolactone)-based wound dressing
column43:
The development of biomimetic materials for use in the human body has been a point of interest for researchers over the past several decades. A prominent process for this is electrospinning because one can spin several components together into a non-woven nanofiber scaffold, similar to the architecture of the extracellular matrix. Polymers such as poly(δ-valerolactone) (PDVL), a biocompatible and biodegradable polyester, and biopolymers such as chitosan, a derivative of chitin known to have antibacterial properties, have been used to make such materials. Our research aimed to develop a collagen analog using a biomimetic PDVL (bPDVL) electrospun with chitosan to make nanofibrous wound dressings. We developed a practical, multi-step synthesis of our monomer, which was then polymerized into a PDVL derivative and modified with amines similar in structure to amino groups found in collagen to produce a bPDVL. Each synthetic step was analyzed using NMR and IR spectroscopies to confirm success. bPDVL/chitosan fiber mats were analyzed via scanning electron microscopy and IR spectroscopy. 
 
Previous studies in the Hamilton lab observed increased hemostatic properties for calcium chloride-treated fiber mats. In the earlier studies, though, the amount of calcium loaded on the scaffolds was unknown. Thus, a quantification method was developed to detect the amount of calcium chloride on the mats so that consistent results on the concentration of loaded calcium chloride could be determined. Additionally, in vitro studies were done on previously made materials to compare the bPDVL fiber mats. In future research, the bPDVL fiber mats will undergo cell and degradation studies to compare to our other fiber mats and similar commercially available products. It is predicted that the mats will help us develop a novel wound dressing that will resemble the extracellular matrix, have antibacterial and hemostatic properties, and be less expensive than a human collagen dressing.

column33: Search For Proteins With Roles in Promoting Spt16 Dissociation From 3’ Ends of Transcribed Genes
column43: Eukaryotic cells use histone chaperones to manipulate chromatin for a variety of processes. FACT (Facilitates Chromatin Transactions) is a highly conserved histone chaperone complex, made of Spt16 and Pob3 in S. cerevisiae, that aids in the disassembly of chromatin so that RNA polymerases can carry out transcription. Our previous research identified a region on nucleosomes known as the ISGI (Influences Spt16-Gene Interactions) region, which is necessary for proper dissociation of Spt16 from the 3’ ends of transcribed genes. In addition to causing Spt16 dissociation defects, the more severe ISGI mutants confer a variety of growth phenotypes, including slow growth, cold sensitivity, and in some cases lethality. Specific mutations in ISGI caused yeast colonies to develop cold sensitivity and/or sickness, were synthetic lethal, or had no effect. Current studies in the lab aim at identifying proteins with possible roles in promoting Spt16 dissociation from genes. Using a synthetic gene array strategy, previous students in the lab identified ~150 proteins that displayed genetic interaction phenotypes with an ISGI mutant suggestive of a role in facilitating Spt16-gene dissociation. Here, I present our progress in these studies and our future plans. We expect these experiments will lead to the identification of one or more factors that promote Spt16 dissociation from chromatin, which is integral to proper gene expression.

column33: Characterization of histone mutants associated with human neurodevelopmental disorders using the yeast model system
column43:
FACT is a highly conserved complex that plays critical roles in various chromosomal processes, including transcription elongation. During elongation, FACT – composed of two proteins, Spt16 and Pob3, in S. cerevisiae – contributes to disassembling nucleosomes in front of Pol II and reassembly following Pol II passage. In previous work, we identified a nucleosomal region – ISGI (Influences Spt16-Gene Interactions) – vital in promoting proper interactions between FACT and transcribed genes. More specifically, mutations within this region cause an accumulation of FACT at the 3’ ends of genes, an effect we attribute to impaired FACT dissociation from genes following transcription. 

Two recent studies have unveiled an association between mutations within one of two genes that encode the human histone H3.3 protein and neurodevelopmental disorders in patients. One of these mutants, H3.3-L61R, corresponds to a strong ISGI mutant, providing a possible link between the neurodevelopmental disorders and FACT-gene disassociation defects. To further explore this potential link and to gain a more general understanding of the effects of human H3.3 mutants on chromatin biology, we are generating yeast cells that carry several of the H3.3 mutations found in the patients with neurodevelopmental disorders. We will then analyze them for defects in FACT-gene interactions and other processes, including cryptic internal transcription initiation, DNA replication, and DNA repair. In this poster, I report on our progress on these projects and describe our experimental plans moving forward.

column33: From Zebrafish Husbandry to Histology: Optimizing Protocols and Establishing an IACUC
column43: Zebrafish (Danio rerio) are freshwater fish native to southern Asia known to be an excellent vertebrate research model. This research model is advantageous because the tissue of zebrafish, aside from the integumentary and respiratory systems, closely resembles human tissue. Therefore, research done with zebrafish is broadly applicable to human biology. Because zebrafish are vertebrates, an Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) must be established at any university wishing to use this research model, to ensure the proper treatment of the animals. This project is focused on creating, optimizing, and compiling lab-specific protocols related to husbandry and histology for both the establishment of an IACUC at Ouachita and for future researchers. In particular, this project involves optimizing protocols for feeding, breeding, and system maintenance, in addition to adapting protocols from peer-reviewed sources on necropsy and histology. While the majority of the protocols have been verified and compiled, the process of establishing an IACUC remains underway, and some histological protocols still need to be optimized. Going forward, this project opens the door for research to be conducted at Ouachita using the zebrafish model and other vertebrate models. Specifically, the planned research will investigate factors of sex differentiation in zebrafish, which is currently not well understood.

column33: Application of isolated mouse cell nuclei as a model for testing apoptotic DNase inhibitors
column43: Apoptotic DNases cause nuclear internucleosomal DNA fragmentation, which is visualized as a 200bp DNA ladder in agarose gels. Overexpression of apoptotic DNases, in particular DNase I and EndoG, in cells and tissues was shown to induce DNA fragmentation. This DNA destruction makes cell death irreversible, while genetic knockout or chemical inhibitors of apoptotic DNases usually prevent cell death. The search for new DNase inhibitors as anti-cell death drugs requires simple quantitative methods for their testing. The goal of the current study was to evaluate isolated cell nuclei as a potential model for testing apoptotic DNase inhibitors and to determine whether DNase I or EndoG directly cause the 200bp ladder. Cell nuclei were isolated by Triton X-100 method from kidneys (expressing DNase I) and brains (with DNase I inactivated by alternative splicing) of wild-type (WT), DNase I knockout (KO), or EndoG KO mice and subjected to autodigestion for varying periods of time from 0 to 240 min in the presence of Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions, which universally activate DNases. Four previously developed inhibitors were tested, including DNase I inhibitors, IG17 and ZnNAC, and EndoG inhibitors, PNR-3-80 and PNR-3-82. DNA was then purified and subjected to 1.4% agarose gel electrophoresis. The gels were stained with ethidium bromide, photographed, and quantified by densitometry using the ImageJ program. EndoG KO or inhibitors did not affect the 200bp-ladder DNA fragmentation, indicating that EndoG is not directly involved in it. DNase I KO slightly mitigated DNA fragmentation by only 5-10% compared to WT, but strongly inhibited DNA fragmentation in the brain. Importantly, DNase I inhibitors strongly inhibited DNA fragmentation (likely due to effects on several DNases). In conclusion, the isolated nuclei model is applicable for testing apoptotic DNase inhibitors. DNase I but not EndoG seems to be partially involved in DNA fragmentation in isolated normal cell nuclei.

column33: Determining the Change in the mRNA Expression of Genes related to Intestinal Permeability During Long term Consumption of High Fat High Sucrose Diet
column43:
Disturbance in the gastrointestinal homeostasis, specifically the disruption of the intestinal barrier plays an important role in the development and progression of extraintestinal diseases. Towards this the intestinal barrier effects and its role in the gut-liver axis is an emerging area of research in the Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD). The NAFLD is also associated with the life-style factors such as a high fat, high sugar diets. In an earlier study* 25 strains of Cross Collaborative mice (a population of mice designed to approximate the genetic variability of the human population; hereon called CC mice), showed strain and sex-specific differences in the development of liver pathologies when fed high fat, high sucrose diet (HF/HS) for 16 weeks. The current study is focused to delineate if there are differences in the intestinal permeability in two strains of CC mice (CC042 and CC011) that showed highly distinguished responses to the diet. Moreover, in this study, a longitudinal assessment of long-term (20, 40 and 60 weeks) consumption of HF/HS diet was conducted to see the impact in the progression of changes (if any) at the gastrointestinal tract. 
Banked samples (ileum tissue ) from male and female mice fed either control or HF/HS diets for 20, 40, and 60 weeks, mice were used in this study. RNA from the ileum was extracted from the ileal mucosa, converted to cDNA to determine mRNA expression of the genes involved in gut permeability using Real Time PCR. The fold change in the gene expression in the HF/HS diet as compared to control, for each of the time point groups were then computed using the gene globe analysis tool to determine changes in gene expression. The data has suggested that a high fat, high sucrose diet affects the expression of genes responsible for gut permeability. Detailed comparison of diet effect (20, 40 and 60 weeks) in these two CC strains is ongoing and will be presented.

column33: Inflammatory cytokine analysis of diet induced non-alcoholic fatty liver (NAFL) disease in murine serum and tissue
column43: Non-alcoholic fatty liver (NAFL) disease is an illness characterized by excessive fat accumulation in the liver and is a growing epidemic in the United States. A 2021 study of NAFL prevalence by the US Fatty Liver Index found a 20% increase in NAFL from 1988-1944, and a 31.9% increase from 2013-2016 (1), demonstrating the escalating pervasiveness. NAFL can progress to non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH), mainly caused by inflammation. We used a mouse model to evaluate the progression of NAFL-induced inflammation in blood serum and livers of male and female mice fed a high fat/high sucrose (HF/HS) diet or control diet for 20, 40, and 60 weeks. To determine the changes of inflammatory markers in mice serum, we measured the quantity of 36 analytes using the Luminex intelliflex multiplexer. We found that 23 of the 36 analytes had significantly different quantities in the serum after HF/HS diet compared to control diet. We observed an increase in significantly different analyte levels after HF/HS diet in blood serum at 40 weeks (63%) for both male and female mice, compared to 20 weeks (27%) and 60 weeks (10%). Analysis of inflammation analytes in liver tissue revealed significantly different quantities after HF/HS diet in 31 of the 36 analytes. Similar to blood serum, we observed that the majority of analytes exhibited changes after 40 weeks (44%) of HF/HS diet in male and female mice, compared to 20 weeks (25%) and 60 weeks (31%). These results are in agreement with liver pathology, which indicated an increase in inflammation in mice fed an HF/HS diet for 40 weeks. In conclusion, we have found that HF/HS diet-induced inflammation occurs in both male and female mice, with the peak window of detectable inflammatory signs occurring at 40 weeks of diet exposure.

column33: Chemical manipulations of rifamycin core provide new solutions to an old problem: Multidrug-resistant tuberculosis
column43:
Chemical manipulations of rifamycin core provide new solutions
to an old problem: Multidrug-resistant tuberculosis

Braden Glenn, Wyatt Treadway, Clara Nikkel, Lola Beeser, Ryan Holdiness, Isabella Beasley, Daniel Armstrong, Marissa Fullerton, Daniel Voth, Irosha Nawarathne

In 1999, the World Health Organization estimated that one-third of the population had latent tuberculosis (TB) infection. This has since been updated to one-fourth of the world. The danger of TB is amplified by mutations which can result in antibiotic resistance. Long term use or misuse of an antibiotic acts as a selection force for bacteria that are drug resistant, which necessitates the development of new drugs. Rifamycin, particularly rifampicin, has been a mainstay of TB treatment since the 1960’s; it binds the 𝛃 subunit of the MBT RNA polymerase (RNAP) and blocks RNA synthesis. Amid the antibiotic resistance crisis, Mycobacterium tuberculosis (MTB)–the pathogen causing TB– has shown widespread resistance to rifampicin, making it futile in TB therapy as MTB RNAP mutations disrupt key interactions between the drug and the target. By utilizing the ‘enabling reaction’ of the rifamycin core and coupling it with click chemistry, we have exploited the thoroughly studied rifamycin scaffold to target MDR-TB and potentially treat other bacterial infections. Our work highlights the first report of synthesis, isolation, and purification of rifamycin derivatives with azido, alkyne and triazole functionalities, the innovative products of coupling complex rifamycin chemistry and simple click chemistry.

column33: Development of a Noncovalent Fluorophore Conjugation Method for Histidine Tagged Proteins
column43: Fluorescence-based assays are powerful experimental tools for studying molecular mechanisms of protein action in biomedical research. Many fluorescence-based methods require fluorescent dyes to be attached to proteins in a stoichiometrically defined, site specific, and stable manner. Covalent attachment of fluorophores to proteins is site specific and stable, but to achieve single-site specificity, protein mutations or peptide ligations are often required. To date, there has not been widespread use of non-covalent labeling strategies. Because many proteins are purified using a histidine tag, non-covalent labeling strategies that target histidine tags could find widespread use. We have identified an RNA aptamer from the literature that has picomolar affinity for histidine tagged proteins. We hypothesize that this RNA aptamer can be used for labeling histidine tagged proteins with a fluorophore. Here, we characterize the interaction between the RNA aptamer and histidine tagged proteins and demonstrate the utility of this fluorophore labeling scheme with proof-of-principle fluorescence experiments.  The universality of the histidine tag as a purification method makes this labeling strategy particularly appealing. In addition, the aptamers can be readily obtained commercially conjugated to a large selection of labels.

column33: Copper-resistant genes in Salmonella enterica serovar enterica play a role in the evasion of host immune response
column43:
Copper plays a crucial role in innate immunity and host defense against microbial pathogens. Copper has been shown to disrupt crucial cellular functions such as amino acid synthesis and DNA replication via displacement of Fe from Fe-S clusters. Alternatively, the reaction of copper with hydrogen peroxide in phagocytic cells leads to the generation of reactive radicals and ions, which exhibit potent antimicrobial properties due to damage they cause to proteins and nucleic acids within the cell. Therefore, pathogens have evolved intricate mechanisms to overcome copper toxicity through sequestration and extrusion of excess intracellular copper.

Understanding the mechanism underlying copper resistance in Salmonella strains provides valuable insights into the development of effective strategies to combat this pathogen and could pave the way for the development of innovative therapeutics.  

Here we show that one isolate of Salmonella enterica serovar enterica isolated from retail meat carries copper-resistant genes, which conferred resistance to 1mM CuCl2 and enhanced survival in macrophages.

column33: The Effects of BT-GSI
column43: Multiple Myeloma (MM) is a hematological cancer that forms in plasma cells, which accumulate in the bone marrow and overgrow normal blood cells. The result of this includes bone loss and fractures. Notch signaling contributes to MM growth. Gamma Secretase Inhibitors (GSI) inhibit Notch signaling and were previously thought of as a possible solution to treat MM. However, GSIs cause a variety of toxic side effects such as severe gut toxicity and have failed in clinical trials. Therefore, the Delgado-Calle Lab developed a therapy which inhibits Notch named Bone-Targeted Gamma Secretase Inhibitor (BT-GSI). BT-GSI specifically targets bone, and consequently does not have severe side effects like GSI does. Because this drug is so recent, there is still speculation of its body distribution, as well as how it impacts the bone. Through the use of pharmacokinetics, I plan to study how the drug distributes in the body and if it accumulates in the bone over time. I will also use microCT imaging to study the effect BT-GSI has on the skeleton of mice with MM. My summer research in both of these fields will provide critical data to determine the effects of BT-GSI therapy.

column33: The Fluorino Version 2: An Open-Source, Arduino Controlled Fluorometer
column43: Fluorometers, used for measuring chemical compound fluorescence intensities and spectra, are commonly used in chemistry, biochemistry, and biophysics educational curricula and research. However, the high cost of purchasing and maintaining research-grade fluorometers restricts their implementation in education and research laboratories. We propose an open-source, Arduino-controlled fluorometer, which we call the Fluorino Version 2 (V2), to provide an affordable and functional alternative to commercial fluorometers. The Fluorino V2 can be easily built using 3D printable optomechanical components, inexpensive optical and electrical hardware, an Arduino Mega 2560 microcontroller, and open-source computer software. This instrument is built from open-source, 3D printable optomechanical components. Our instrument is controlled by our provided Arduino IDE and processing code and software. To test the device, we performed fluorescence measurements on both the Fluorino V2 and a commercial fluorometer to compare the measurements of the spectroscopic intensities of various fluorescein concentrations among both devices. Demonstrated by the functionality and accessibility of the Fluorino V2, this instrument can be easily implemented into educational curricula—granting students both a functional and “under the hood” understanding of fluorescence instrumentation.

column33: Role of the PTH1 receptor in osteocytes in a preclinical model of Type 2 diabetes
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: As of 2021, an estimated 537 million people across the world, making up 6.8% of the global population are affected by diabetes mellitus (DM). DM has a degenerative effect on bone, and diabetic patients have a higher risk of bone fracture compared to normoglycemic individuals.  Bone mineral density (BMD) is significantly reduced in Type 1 (T1DM) patients, and unaffected or even higher in T2DM patients; however, in both conditions bone formation rate is low, and bone microarchitecture is compromised. Recent experiments using a pre-clinical mouse model demonstrated that two of the FDA approved bone anabolic agents, (ligands of the PTH1R), parathyroid hormone (PTH), and the PTHrP analog abaloparatide (ABL) restored bone lost and increased bone quality in T2DM mice.  However, it is still not clear which cells are responsible for the anabolic effects of PTH and ABL in T2DM mice. The current study utilizes DMP1-8kb-Cre mice to conditionally knock out (cKO) the PTH1R in osteocytes. DEXA analysis shows that in both control and cKO mice, the total BMD was reduced by T2DM, indicating that the removal of PTH1R from the osteocytes does not impact T2DM pathological effects in bone. Ongoing analysis of BMD will determine if the removal of PTH1R from the osteocyte will alter the regenerative effects of PTH and ABL on diabetic bone.

column33: Biological Rocketry
column43:
Science Division, Lyon College, 2300 Highland Rd., Batesville, AR 72501

Model and High-power rocketry can be used to conduct scientific experiments. These experiments often make use of the payload section of the rocket, which can hold relevant technology or specimens. Our research team has used rocketry to conduct biological research. 
During the summers of 2022 and 2023, we made progress in our research with the LADCAP (Launchable Automatic Device for Collecting Airborne Particles). The LADCAP is made up of a vacuum pump which draws air through a hole in the side of the rocket and then through a filter. The filter catches airborne microbes that can later be cultured and identified. The vacuum is instructed by an onboard flight computer to begin collecting samples after a particular amount of time from launch. This system could potentially be used with a wide range of craft, but our air-testing has been conducted with the custom-built mid-power rocket G-Lifter, the scratch-built high-power rocket The Highlander, the Madcow Adventurer, and the LOC Precision Hi-Tech. LADCAP collects high-altitude microorganisms which can withstand extremes including temperature, low pressure, desiccation, and increased UV flux. The particles are thusly considered extremophiles. The data collected about extremophiles on earth can potentially be extrapolated to extremophiles in other locations, including those elsewhere in the solar system. Biological research with the LADCAP system and rocketry is contained within the designation of “aeromicrobiology.”
This research is supported with grants from the Arkansas Space Grant Consortium.

column33: Synthesis of Pyridine-fused Benzothiophene To Generate a Library of Novel Bioactive Compounds
column43: Antibiotic resistance is a global concern as it makes existing antibiotics ineffective against bacterial infection. Every year, in the United States, more than 2.8 million people have infected by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, and it causes more than 35,000 deaths annually. One of the goals of the CDC to tackle antibiotic resistance is to develop novel antibiotics. Benzothiophene is a biologically active molecule, and it is found in different approved drugs such as Benocyclidine,  Sertaconazole, Rolaxifene, and Zileuton. We have reacted several derivatives of 2-Fluorobenzonitrile with 2,5-dihydroxy-1,4-dithiane, and it formed a β-aminocarbonyl group containing benzothiophenes. The β-aminocarbonyl group provided us to synthesize a series of novel compounds. A series of [1]benzothieno[3,2-b]pyridine was produced by reacting the benzothiophene with different acetophenones, and 2-ketones. All of the compounds provided good yields and were characterized by 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopy. The compounds will be tested against different drug-resistant bacteria including methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) and vancomycin-resistant enterococci (VRE) for their antibacterial activity and results will be presented.
