column33: Determination of whether human Rev1 mediates G4-associated replication gap suppression
column43: G-quadruplexes (G4s) are non-canonical nucleic acid structures that form in guanine-rich regions of DNA and RNA. G4 structures can present an endogenous barrier to replication fork progression. Failure to bypass G4s during DNA replication results in an increase in single-stranded DNA (ssDNA), which can lead to genomic instability. Rev1 is a translesion synthesis (TLS) polymerase that disrupts and replicates G4 DNA, though the precise mechanism is unclear. We seek to elucidate the relationship between human Rev1 (hRev1) and replication gap suppression near G4 sites. To test the effects of hRev1 loss on G4-associated ssDNA formation, we will perform non-denaturing immunofluorescence detection of two thymidine analogs, 5-chloro-2’-deoxyuridine (CldU) and 5-ethynyl-2’-deoxyuridine (EdU), in WT and REV1KO cells. We aim to further explore the relationship between replication stress near G4 sites and hRev1 using proximity ligation assay experiments, in which we will investigate whether the presence of hRev1 affects the formation of G4 structures near (i) ssDNA and (ii) components of the replisome. Our findings have implications for novel cancer therapies that target TLS pathways, as well as mechanisms that bypass endogenous fork barriers.

column33: Oxygen uptake and heart rate during rest and exercise in children with normal weight or obesity
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Background: Childhood obesity continues to be a problem in the United States. Many children are eating high-calorie, low-nutrient foods, and have low levels of  physical activity. These children are more likely to carry over their obesity into adulthood—becoming more prone to clinical risks for cardiometabolic diseases such as cardiovascular disease, high cholesterol, and high blood pressure. It is unclear if there are differences between physiological responses to exercises when comparing children with obesity and normal-weight. This current study aims to assess whether there is a correlation between heart rate and oxygen (O2) uptake in children 8-11 years old during rest and submaximal exercise. Methods: The data being used is from a study where heart rate was measured using a metabolic cart during rest and during 30 min biking at either 30 Watts or at a workload corresponding to 40% of their peak O2 uptake. Using Pearson Correlation Factor  data is being analyzed to find out whether there is a positive, negative, or no correlation. Between O2 uptake and heart rate at rest and at submaximal exercise. Data is divided into two separate categories of girls and boys with normal weight or obesity. Results: As of now, comparisons are still being made to conclude this study. Conclusion: With these data we will learn about how normal weight and obesity respond to exersice. This can help health and fitness professionals designing health plans that best fit the child on their fitness journey and help them adopt a healthier lifestyle for their long-term health.

column33: In Vitro Characterization of Novel VSV-derived Oncolytic Vectors Targeting Hyaluronic Acid and Collagen in Pancreatic Ductal Adenocarcinoma.
column43: The prognoses and clinical outcomes of patients with pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) are among the worst in oncology, with a median survival of less than 1 year from diagnosis. This is in part due to the desmoplastic and poorly perfused stroma of PDAC characterized by overexpression of hyaluronic acid (HA) and collagen (CN), which significantly impair drug delivery and infiltration of immune cells into tumor tissues. Vesicular stomatitis virus (VSV), a widely used vesiculovirus, has shown tremendous clinical potential as an oncolytic agent in several in vivo models of pancreatic cancer. VxG, a novel hybrid VSV-derived oncolytic vector lacks the neurotoxicity associated with VSV treatment and retains the fast kinetics and potent cytotoxic effects of VSV. The goal of this study was to provide in vitro characterization of the oncolytic activity of VxG-based vectors expressing tumor-degrading enzymes. Vectors engineered to express mouse PH20, collagenase, both mouse PH20 and collagenase, as well as serraptidase were analyzed. Through TCID50 assays, the engineered VxG-based vectors were shown to have comparable infectivity to the parent virus. Further, cell viability assays and crystal violet performed on a susceptible, moderate, and resistant mouse pancreatic cell line demonstrated clear oncolytic activity among all viruses. These findings suggest that the enzyme expressing VxG vectors produce viable infection in PDAC cell lines and are promising candidates for in vivo testing. Ongoing studies will utilize mouse models to determine whether targeting HA and CN in tumor stroma maximizes the oncolytic activity of VxG and increases immune cell infiltration in the tumor microenvironment.

column33: Structural analysis of inhibitor-bound mitogen-activated protein kinases-interacting kinases 1 and 2 using X-ray crystallography
column43: Mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPK)-interacting kinases 1 and 2 (MNK1 and MNK2) regulate expression of cell cycle proteins, and excess upregulation of these two kinases can lead to oncogenesis, local invasion, and metastasis. In this study, we aim to use X-ray crystallography to determine the molecular basis for the selectivity of a newly discovered inhibitor for MNK1 and MNK2. We began by transforming bacteria with a DNA plasmid coding for an MNK attached to a glutathione S-transferase (GST) tag. Cells were lysed and centrifuged leaving the water-soluble MNK in the supernatant, which was mixed with glutathione beads that bound to the GST-tagged MNK. Afterwards, the MNK was purified by washing the bead-protein complex, cleaving the GST tag, and filtering the MNK. We further purified the sample via anion-exchange chromatography, separating solutes by charge using an anion gradient. Once the protein was isolated, we prepared an array of solutions to find one that will allow the MNK molecules to crystallize. This will enable us to fire X-rays onto the MNK crystals and utilize the diffraction pattern to calculate the 3D structure. Finding the structural basis for this inhibitor’s binding to MNK1 will allow us to design better drugs for MNKs to suppress their oncogenic effects.

column33: Microbiological survey of commercial tattoo and permanent makeup inks available in the United States
column43: In three previous surveys of tattoo inks on the market done by the FDA, 39% (62 out of 159 inks) of tattoo and permanent makeup inks (PMU) were found to have bacterial contamination with some pathogenic species having the potential to cause infections if injected into the skin. The present study aims to expand upon these findings by increasing the sample size and including inks from various manufacturers. We surveyed 10 tattoo and PMU inks (five tattoo inks and five PMU inks) from different manufacturers. The inks were tested for bacterial and fungal contamination using the aerobic plating and enrichment methodologies outlined in FDA’s Bacteriological Analytical Manual (BAM) Chapter 23 “Methods for Cosmetics.” Briefly, inks were first diluted in Modified Letheen Broth (MLB) and then plated on Modified Letheen Agar (MLA) and Potato Dextrose Agar (PDA) plates to test for bacterial and fungal contamination, respectively. In parallel, diluted ink samples were first enriched in MLB for seven days and then plated on MLA to ensure any microbial contamination within the ink sample would be identified. Plates were incubated at 30℃ for 2-7 days and examined for microbial contamination. Isolated bacteria were lysed, and the cell lysate was used for PCR amplification of the 16S rRNA gene. The species of the bacteria was identified by the 16S rRNA gene sequence. The experiments are ongoing; currently, four samples have been found to be contaminated with five different bacteria.

The nanoplatforms consist of gold nanocages with surface functionalized with "smart" polymer which can response to internal or external stimuli for on-demand release of therapeutics. column33: Developing Accurate QSAR Models to Predict Ames Mutagenicity
column43: An Ames Test is a bacterial reverse mutation assay designed to detect a wide range of chemical substances that can cause gene mutations and is used to determine the mutagenic potential (ability to cause mutations) of new chemicals and drugs. Quantitative structure-activity relationship (QSAR) models can be used to predict Ames mutagenicity and are used in place of actual toxicological studies. The goal of this study is to build a reliable model that is able to accurately predict Ames mutagenicity and specifically determine how increasing the sample size of the training dataset impacts how well the model performs on the test dataset. We first conducted data cleaning and removed the chemicals that the model cannot handle from the training datasets and used the cleaned datasets to obtain molecular descriptors that describe molecular structure in numeric form. The next step was feature preprocessing where molecular descriptors with low variance and high correlation was removed from the training data to improve model performance. Then, parameter optimization was conducted on 5 different algorithms (logistic regression, KNN, SVM, random forest, and XGBoost) to determine which parameters resulted in the best model performance for each algorithm. The algorithms and optimized parameters were then used to build a model and assess how the performance changed when providing more of the training data as input. So far, the results show that XGBoost has the best model performance when given one part of the training data as input due to the high F1 score, MCC, specificity, sensitivity, and accuracy and we are working towards obtaining the model performance results when including the rest of the training data as input.  Building accurate QSAR models to predict Ames mutagenicity is important and can save money and increase efficiency when it comes to determining the safety of chemicals.

column33: Isolating and Characterizing Gordonia Bacteriophage
column43: Bacteriophages are viruses that kill bacterial cells by inserting their DNA and replicating inside of the cell. People should be more aware and educated about bacteriophages because right now overseas, they are being used as antibiotics in humans to help kill bacterial infections that they have. I am researching how to find and isolate bacteriophages. This process is called enrichment. You will collect soil samples or whatever environmental sample you have, then go through the process of shaking a phage off of the sample and isolating and filtering the phages. You will then do spot titers to either confirm or deny that you have found a bacteriophage in your samples. Once you have the results, you will either collect more samples if you do not have a bacteriophage present, or you will continue with the process of making sure that you have only one virus. The next step will be to test the bacterial host range of the bacteriophage to see how well it infects related species of bacteria. You will then extract the bacteriophage DNA to upload the sequence to the Actinobacteriophage Database to name and compare your bacteriophage to others. Hopefully, in the future of medicine, we can use bacteriophages to help cure microbial diseases.

column33: 3D Printable Library of Optomechanical Components: An Affordable Alternative to Commercial Optical Products
column43: Over the last several decades, 3D printing, otherwise known as additive manufacturing, has become a standard in open-source hardware development. Fused Filament Fabrication (FFF) 3D printers, specifically, have provided many scientists and engineers with affordable alternatives to developing and customizing parts for experiments and prototypes. FFF is a type of 3D printing in which thermoplastic filament is extruded through a hot, mechanized nozzle and laid onto a platform in successive layers to eventually produce a desired object from an uploaded Computer Aided Design (CAD) file. Because many scientific applications require specialized parts that are oftentimes expensive to purchase or to maintain, being able to 3D print customized components for scientific instrumentation can potentially save time (commercial manufacturing and shipping) and money, as FFF 3D printing only requires one moderately priced 3D printer. Here, we present a library of 3D printable optomechanical components. These 3D printable components are near identical to as well as fully compatible with commercial optomechanical components; the library includes posts, post holders, bases, lens mounts, kinematic optics mounts, LED holders, and a breadboard holder. These components were tested for optical functionality and stability in entirely 3D printable optical systems, and we further demonstrate the systems’ comparability in performance to their commercial counterparts. Therefore, we expect this library of 3D printable optomechanical components to be compatible in scientific research and educational laboratories.

column33: Analyzing a Degradable Natural Polymer-Based Novel Wound Dressing for Use in Biomedical Applications
column43: Modern research towards wound dressings has shown that alternatives to standard bandages have proven more successful at healing injuries. One such method is the use of an electrospun fiber mat. Polymers can be spun into a construct that has a random configuration of fibers which closely resembles the architecture of the extracellular matrix. Furthermore, changing the polymer composition of the mat allows nanofiber to  facilitate  wound healing . Some of the polymers used also have a natural degradation rate that eradicates the need for dressing removal – particularly with respect to internal dressings. In this experiment, the natural polymer alginate was modified to create an ideal compound for wound dressings. Amines similar to amino acids in collagen were attached to the alginate to make it biomimetic and to yield free amines which are known to have antibacterial properties. This modified  alginate (bAlg) was  then oxidized to increase its rate of degradation in physiological conditions. Modified alginate was analyzed via IR spectroscopy to verify the successful attachment of amines. Percent oxidation was determined through the use of an indicator. After modification, the biomimetic, oxidized alginate (oxbAlg) was electrospun with polyvinyl alcohol (PVA) and the fiber mats were analyzed  in vitro . In vitro cell studies were run over a period of weeks and the effect of the modified alginate on the cells was observed. Future tests will be run to test the degradation rate of the oxbAlg.

column33: Random Forest Model for Predicting µ Opioid Receptor Binding Activity for Assisting Development of Opioid Drugs
column43: The opioid epidemic is one of the most prominent and severe public health crises in U.S. history. The devastating consequences of the opioid crisis are not only the increased number of deaths caused by opioids but also the increased economic burden of combating this crisis. The highly addictive nature of the opioids is closely related to the overdose fatalities caused by prescription opioids, heroin, and illicit fentanyl. However, the therapeutic benefits of prescription opioids acting as the most potent analgesic make prohibition of the drug impossible. Opioids exert its analgesic effect by binding to the µ opioid receptor (MOR), which then activates its downstream signaling pathway, eventually leading to the inhibition of spinal cord pain transmission. Since the discovery of MOR in the 1970s, many efforts have been endeavored to understand the structure activity relationship between the receptor and its ligands, hoping to shed some lights on the development of non- or less-addictive opioid analgesics. Yet, many questions remain unanswered, and the development of non- or less-addictive opioid analgesics has had limited success. Here, we present a machine learning model that can be used to predict the binding activity of small molecule compounds to the MOR based on chemical structures. The random forest models were evaluated using 5-fold cross validations and were challenged with the testing data set, resulting in good MOR binding activity prediction accuracy in the cross validations and testing, respectively. Our results suggest that this model could be useful to identify novel MOR binders, which may aid the development of new drugs targeting on MOR.

column33: Analyzing the Host Range of Gordonia bacteriophages
column43: Bacteriophages are viruses that infect bacteria. This research consists of characterizing the host range of temperate phages of the bacteria genus Gordonia. The host range of three Gordonia bacteriophages (Grandslam, Ruthy, and Goib) was observed using three species of Gordonia bacteria - the isolation host G. terrae CAG3, and the expansion hosts G. rubripertincta and G. lacunae. The phages were observed using spot titers on PYCa agar plates. The spot titers were used to calculate plaque forming units per milliliter (pfu/mL). The pfu/mL values on the expansion hosts, G. lacunae and G. rubripertincta, were compared against the pfu/mL value on the isolation host, G. terrae CAG3, to get an efficiency of plating value (EOP). Results have shown that all phages have an EOP value substantially less than one on the expansion hosts.  All samples using G. lacunae and some samples using G. rubripertincta resulted in killing from without. Once the baseline EOP values are established, these phages will be co-cultured following the Appelman protocol in an effort to increase their EOP on the expansion hosts.

column33: Quantification of Gordonia terrae Bacteriophages using Lysate qPCR
column43: Bacteriophages are viruses that infect and replicate only in bacterial cells. Quantitative PCR was used in this experiment to count the number of DNA copies in the phage lysate sample. In this project, the more rapid lysate qPCR method was compared to standard plate count titer assays using the double layer agar method, to match the number of genomic copies with the plaque-forming units in the lysate. Initially, multiple primer sets were designed to amplify the phage tape measure gene and assessed at various annealing temperatures to determine the best primers and reaction conditions to use for phage detection.  Because qPCR is sensitive to contamination, there were multiple controls to ensure no contamination. Subsequently, a standard curve was generated by comparing the phage concentration determined from titer assays with that measured using SYBR Green qPCR. The optimized lysate qPCR method will be a faster method to determine the number of bacteriophage DNA copies in phage lysate, allowing the rapid determination of phage concentration for optical density-based infection growth curve experiments.

column33: “Metabolism of Pexidartinib and it’s Potential Cause of Liver Toxicity via Bioactivation”
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKI) are used in the treatment of many  types of cancer targeting cancer-specific pathways to minimize damage to healthy cells. Pexidartinib is a type of TKI that has been commonly used to treat rare types of cancers like tenosynovial giant cell tumor (TGCT). While effective in the clinic, p exidartinib has been shown to cause severe liver toxicity through an unknown mechanism. It is hypothesized  that pexidartinib undergoes bioactivation into a quinone. This reactive metabolite could then trigger direct hepatotoxicity and/or harmful immune response. This hypothesis is being tested with metabolic reactions for pexidartinib with lapatinib as a positive TKI control since the drug has published results to undergo bioactivation in the same conditions. Both TKIs will be metabolized using human liver microsomes (HLM) and the reactive quinones trapped with glutathione and the resulting adducts analyzed by LC-MS. Experiments will be carried out with fluorescently labeled dansyl-glutathione, so that the amount of adduct that forms can be quantitated. Currently, preliminary data has been collected to support the possible formation of the expected adduct. Knowing whether pexidartinib undergoes bioactivation or not will justify further research into its metabolic phenotyping and kinetics. If the major enzymes responsible for metabolism can be identified, then assessing risk from patient to patient can be inferred from the known relationship between demographics and variation in those enzymes. Also, if the kinetics and metabolic pathway of the adduct can further be studied, a treatment can be developed to mitigate liver toxicity, allowing patients to receive all the cancer treatment benefits while minimizing damage to the liver by blocking metabolic pathways that form quinones.

column33: Nutrition Assessment of Preschool and School Age Children
column43: Obesity in children is a nationwide issue. In Arkansas, 14.2% of children ages 2-4 and 20% of children ages 10-17 are obese. column33: Attacking the Origin: Targeting Cancer Stem Cells using Sesquiterpene Lactones
column36: Arkansas School for Mathematics, Sciences, and the Arts
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Glioblastoma (GBM) is the most common and aggressive malignant brain tumor. Treatment options are limited to chemotherapy, radiation, and surgical resection. The lethality of the tumor lies not only in its aggressiveness, but its perseverance. Recurrence of GBM is almost inevitable in most of the GBM patients, usually with the tumor developing therapy resistance. Cancer Stem Cells (CSC), a subset of tumor cells, contribute to tumor relapse by causing tumor initiation. These cells could differentiate into multiple types of cells to maintain a tumor. They are usually treatment-resistant, and often more aggressive. A promising new way to target CSC is to use sesquiterpene lactones (SLs), which are naturally occurring compounds. SLs have anticancer properties by inducing NF-κB gene expression and reacting with thiols in cancer cells. A common thiol, glutathione detoxifies hydroperoxides in cells. Loss of glutathione and the alteration of gene expression causes CSCs to become increasingly sensitive to oxidative stress, leading to a form of cell death named ferroptosis. The aim of the current study is to determine the cytotoxic effects of various SLs in multiple human GBM cell lines (LN18, T98G, U87). We performed MTT viability assays and imaged-based measurements of cell number and confluency utilizing an Incucyte Live Cell imaging. Our first experiments revealed that parthenolide (PTL) and dehyroleucodine (DHL) showed similar IC50 doses (between 5 and 10 uM). Our next step was to plate clonogenic numbers of cells with the control being 400 cells with 1 uM, 5 uM, and 10 uM treatments. We found that the control plates had an average of 96 clones and the 5uM plates with 800 cells had an average of 115.5 supporting our approximate IC50 value between 5 uM and 10 uM. We will move forward to assess SLs ability to eradicate the CSCs using different GMB CSC markers.

column33: Identifying the effect of CARD11 G4-stabilization on NF-𝜅B signaling in activated B cell lymphomas
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: The activated B cell (ABC) subtype of diffuse large B cell lymphoma (DLBCL) is an aggressive, often chemoresistant cancer associated with dysregulation of the B cell receptor (BCR) pathway. Key components of the BCR pathway include the transcription factor NF-𝜅B and an NF-𝜅B regulatory protein, CARD11. Activation and nuclear translocation of the NF-𝜅B p65 subunit through phosphorylation promotes the expression of pro-survival oncogenes overexpressed in ABC-DLBCL such as MYC and BCL2. Given the crucial role of CARD11 in facilitating NF-𝜅B activation, we hypothesize that CARD11 repression can decrease NF- 𝜅B p65 phosphorylation, thereby mitigating the expression of anti-apoptotic genes. This lab has previously repressed CARD11 by stabilizing a DNA secondary structure known as a G-quadruplex (G4) in its promoter region. G4s are formed by the folding of guanine-rich DNA into stacked tetrads and are well-known for their ability to alter the transcription of nearby genes. A small molecule that selectively binds and stabilizes the CARD11 G4 was demonstrated to reduce CARD11 transcription in lymphoma cells. To investigate our hypothesis that CARD11 G4-stabilization inhibits NF-𝜅B p65 phosphorylation and the activity of pro-survival genes, two ABC-DLBCL cell lines, RIVA and HBL1, were treated with either a CARD11 G4-stabilizing molecule or a vehicle and subjected to global and phospho-proteomics.  Proteomic analysis is being performed using the QIAGEN Ingenuity Pathway Analysis and Proteoviz softwares to identify differentially expressed proteins and predict pathways altered in the CARD11 - NF-𝜅B signaling axis. We will also determine whether repressing CARD11 directly inhibits NF 𝜅B activation by using immunoblotting to quantify phosphorylated p65 in control cells versus CARD11 G4-stabilized cells. Understanding the role of CARD11 and NF-𝜅B p65 in BCR signaling may uncover more effective molecular targets for the treatment of ABC-lymphomas.

column33: Decoding the Leukocyte Transcriptome: Insights into the Dynamic Progression and Relapse Patterns of Multiple Myeloma
column43: Multiple Myeloma (MM) is an incurable cancer that affects the plasma cells. The mechanisms of carcinogenesis are relatively unknown, hindering development of effective treatments. Moreover, MM is characterized by cycles of relapse, where remission from treatment is often followed by faster cancer progression and increased drug resistance. Studies have emphasized the importance of bone marrow microenvironment changes in addressing this feature of myeloma relapse and drug response. Specifically, CD14/CD16 monocytes and CD8 T lymphocytes undergo significant proportion changes during MM progression. This study aims to identify potential cell subsets and genetic differences within leukocytes in patients with early MM relapse compared to those without relapse in order to learn about the mechanisms behind disease progression and drug resistance. For this study, bone marrow aspirate and peripheral blood cells were collected from patients with early relapse (n=4) and no relapse (n=3) at various treatment timepoints. Single-cell RNA sequencing was performed, and Seurat workflow was used for data processing. CD8, CD14, and CD16 cell data were isolated, undergoing normalization, PCA, SCT, and integration, for further clustering analysis. The analysis revealed 9 distinct subclusters within CD14/CD16 monocytes, and 7 within CD8 lymphocytes. Differential expression analysis based on relapse status identified several genes of interest, including FOSB, IL8, IL1B, and HLA genes, which are also consistent with the genes expressed highly in clusters where the proportion of cells increased or decreased substantially. These results build upon previous research that indicates that these genes of interest are involved in the promotion of cancer growth and osteoclastogenesis. Moreover, they suggest that specific subgroups of cells within leukocytes populations play a more significant role in MM relapse, potentially aiding the development of targeted therapies for MM.

column33: “Synthesizing a novel wound care fiber mat and testing its clotting capabilities”
column43:
For centuries, gauze has been central to wound care and healing. As early as the 1980s, hemostatic dressings have helped stabilize wounds in treating traumatic injuries. However, gauze is a foreign substance to the human body and must be removed over time, which is not ideal for all types of wound healing. Some gauze-based hemostatic systems can also cause secondary burn wounds due to excess chitosan, a required substance for its efficacy. In our study, first we designed a novel wound dressing that should improve on current methods. This dressing mimics the human extracellular matrix which helps cell regeneration and will degrade in the body, eliminating the need to change or remove the dressing following application. The amount of chitosan utilized in our dressing is also reduced, lowering the chances of burns within wounds. A carboxylic acid-modified polycaprolactone (PCL) was produced and subsequently modified via amide coupling reactions to produce a biomimetic PCL (bPCL). bPCL was electrospun with chitosan to produce fiber mats ready for testing and analysis as a wound dressing. 
The second part of the project focused on the design and construction of a device that would simulate an “open wound” environment using 3-D printing and polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS). Such a device allows the clotting properties of the dressing to be tested. Specifically, the device would allow the Hamilton lab to perform flow tests to analyze the clotting capabilities of fiber mats. Future studies will analyze the hemostatic properties of the bPCL/chitosan fiber mats by pumping samples of platelets through the device with the fiber mat placed inside.

column33: The impact of toll-like receptor 8 (TLR8) on vesicular trafficking and foam cell formation
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: A third of all deaths in the United States are attributed to atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD), a chronic disease defined by progressive, lipid-rich plaque growth within arterial walls. Elevated levels of circulating cholesterol on low-density lipoprotein (LDL) are a primary risk factor for ASCVD, as this promotes LDL accumulation within the sub-endothelial space and subsequent capture by macrophages that patrol the vessel micro-environment. Engorgement of macrophages with LDL results in these cells becoming foam cells; a large, dysfunctional, lipid-loaded cell that often becomes necrotic and directly contributes to plaque growth. Therapies that target foam cell dysfunction to treat or prevent ASCVD are in high demand; however, progress is limited by an incomplete understanding of why LDL uptake promotes macrophage dysfunction and foam cell biogenesis. Recently, our group reported that LDL transports small RNA and these non-traditional cargo trigger inflammatory polarization of macrophages by activating toll-like receptor 8 (TLR8), an endosomal sensor of single stranded RNA. Most intriguingly, antagonism of TLR8 reduced ASCVD in hyperlipidemic mice and blunted the formation of foam cells within developing plaques. Here, we have hypothesized that TLR8 contributes to foam cell biogenesis by disrupting endosome-to-lysosome transport of internalized LDL particles. To test this hypothesis, we have developed fluorescent fusion proteins to track TLR8 containing vesicles. Furthermore, we have generated novel fluorescent viral-like particles to both activate TLR8 and visualize pinocytic uptake and transport. These tools have been paired with acquired expertise in confocal microscopy to quantify the impact of TLR8 activation on delivery of pinocytic cargo to lysosomes. Ongoing studies will explore how TLR8-induced changes in vesicular trafficking contribute to LDL-induced foam cell dysfunction.

column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: While Reovirus is a commonly asymptomatic infection in humans, through prior studies of replication and mortality rates in mice models, it has also been found to have a viral linkage to causing myocarditis, an inflammatory heart disease. To make the comparison of its viral replication, this study will focus on the characterization of reovirus pathogenesis in cardiac myocytes (heart muscle cells) by utilizing a human cell line such as AC16 cells. Different reovirus-influenced myocarditis strains, such as the mild, non-lethal strain, T1L, and the typically fatal strain, T1L/T3DM2, will be compared through investigations over their protein production as it allows for pathogen reproduction to occur. In correlation to the experimentations on mice and with the results obtained from this analysis of the differentiating virulent strains, it’ll build the understanding of replication activity of myocarditis caused by reovirus in humans.

column33: Enhancing the National Trauma Data Standard: Improving Definitions and Adding AI Preparedness
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: In the U.S., trauma is the leading cause of death for individuals under the age of 45. Despite standardization of care, at Level I and Level II trauma centers, there remains significant variability in patient outcomes across both levels. The NIH-funded Trauma Institutional Priorities and Teams for Outcomes Efficiency (TIPTOE), links organizational structures in Level 1 and Level 2 centers to patient outcomes as reported by Trauma Quality Improvement Program (TQIP). This study aims to provide ontological representation for TQIP data elements to integrate TQIP data with data on organizational structures. To integrate, the study reconstructed definitions and labels from TQIP’s data dictionary, the National Trauma Data Standard (NTDS), using standard terminological practices. NTDS tends to define circularly, meaning words from the term are in the definition. New definitions follow genus-differentia format: Term is a member of a specific superclass and has unique characteristics. Terms and definitions were implemented in a Web Ontology Language (OWL) file using Protégé Ontology Editor. OWL is a language with formal semantics allowing for description and classification of concepts within a domain enabling a computer to make inferences. Protégé is an app for creating and editing OWL ontologies. For categorization, Basic Formal Ontology (BFO) was imported into the OWL file. BFO is an established ontology with overarching taxonomies serving as an upper level for several other ontologies. Through this process, new definitions and labels were created for 20 NTDS terms. Terms were relabeled to conform to labeling standards for ontology development. Based on the new definitions, 10 of the 20 terms were implemented into an OWL file with BFO imported. Future work will expand this file so terminology can be consumed by a computer. This study highlights changing data elements to have a consistent organization system may improve the efficiency of trauma centers.

column33: Characterization of Burn Injury Influences on Cell Respiration  in Patients With Induced Hypermetabolism
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
“Characterization of Burn Injury Influences on Cell Respiration in Patients With Induced Hypermetabolism” 
Martin Morales,1* LillieTreas,2 Craig Porter,2,3 Jaycelyn Hall,2,3
1University of Arkansas-Little Rock, 3University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences, 2Arkansas Children’s Research Institute
In this study, we are characterizing the influences that burn severity, and time post burn have on mitochondria oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) to further understand the pathways of burn induced hypermetabolism.
Studies show that induced hypermetabolism, present in patients with sepsis and other trauma, is associated with high energy dependent reactions that negatively affect patient recovery. Because hypermetabolism has been detected after trauma like sepsis and chemotherapy by higher protein turnover, and cytokine levels; we hypothesized that samples from burned individuals will present a higher respiration than controls. By comparing samples, we hope to gain insight into the metabolic pathways that can be the early stages for improving therapeutics and overall patient outcomes. Blood samples from 125 adult and pediatric patients will be collected for this purpose. With current samples, Peripheral Blood Mononuclear Cells (PBMCs) have been isolated by centrifugation, and mitochondria (OXPHOS) has been measured using Oroboros O2K High Resolution Respirometry (HRR) instruments. 
We have used Substrate-uncoupler-inhibitor titration (SUIT) protocol RP1 to test mitochondrial function, and core energy metabolism is analyzed by comparing O2 consumption at each substrate injection. Datlab software and spreadsheets for data collection and analysis are being used.
Current results include 7 burn patient samples and 14 control samples. The ratio of O2 flux concentration over the max respiration after the addition of each substrate has been compared to control values using a Box and Whiskers graph. More samples and analysis are needed to get a true comparison of o2 consumption.

column33: Proliferation and Oxygen Production of Arithrospira platensis in Varying Light Intensities
column43: As space travel becomes more advanced, adequate nourishment and oxygen resources are crucial issues for scientists concerning long-term travel. Arithrospira platensis, also known as Spirulina, is a protein-rich cyanobacterium that could potentially provide a solution to these issues with minimal energy consumption. Spirulina is known to be used for protein supplementation with various health benefits and pharmacological applications. In addition, Spirulina cultures produce high amounts of oxygen through the conversion of carbon dioxide into energy. Proliferation and oxygen production are primarily dependent on cell structure (straight or coiled). A mixed culture containing straight and coiled Spirulina cells and a primarily coiled Spirulina culture were studied using 2.5 L containers under 40 µM, 60 µM, and 80 µM light intensities in order to determine the behavior of cell reproduction and its effects on oxygen production. Cell reproduction and oxygen production were monitored in 24-hour intervals. Preliminary results indicate that coiled cultures produced higher cell counts (60,000 cells/mL) than mixed cultures (50,000 cells/mL) at 40-60 μmol light intensities. In regards to oxygen produced per cell, mixed cultures produced more oxygen (0.001 oxygen/cell) than coiled cultures (0.0005 oxygen/cell). These results imply that coiled cells utilize more energy in cellular activities while straight cells utilize more energy during photosynthesis. Additional studies need to be done to determine these differences and to discern which cell structure is most effective for long-term space travel.

column33: The Mitochondrial Ubiquitin Ligase MARCHF5 Regulates Both Apoptosis and Mitochondrial Physiology in Primary Effusion Lymphoma
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Primary Effusion Lymphoma (PEL) is caused by Kaposi's Sarcoma Herpes Virus (KSHV) in the context of AIDS. Our previous work has shown that PEL cells require the expression of the oncogene MCL1, which stops intrinsic apoptosis. Furthermore, related on-going work in our laboratory reveals that MCL1 may synergize with another oncogene MARCHF5. This is surprising since MARCHF5 has not been linked to apoptosis; it is instead known as a mitochondrial E3 ubiquitin ligase that ubiquitinates clients involved in mitochondrial fusion/fission and antiviral sensing. Our goal is to define the function of MARCHF5 in PEL cell lines. Using a PEL cell line with a doxycycline-inducible Cas9, we showed that CRISPR knockout (KO) of MARCHF5 led to a significant decrease of live cells accompanied by increased caspase 3/7 activity. Western blot analysis reveals that the pro-apoptotic protein NOXA is stabilized upon MARCHF5 KO suggesting that MARCHF5 functions to block intrinsic apoptosis. Cell death due to MARCHF5 KO is independent of lytic reactivation or activation of antiviral sensing. Interestingly, staining with mitochondrial dyes followed by flow cytometry revealed that loss of MARCHF5 decreased both mitochondrial content as well as mitochondrial membrane potential.  In sum, our results indicate that in PEL cells, the oncogene MARCHF5 functions to maintain mitochondrial health as well as regulate cell survival by synergizing with MCL1. This should be further studied for a potential therapeutic target for PEL.

column33: Predicting Watermelon Sweetness From Induced Vibrational Frequencies
column43: This project is a continuation of research to determine if the sound frequencies produced from thumping a watermelon can predict its sweetness. Over the past few years, a program has been created in MATLAB to break down the thump signal into its corresponding harmonic frequencies using the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT). These frequencies, along with the weight of the watermelon and other information from the FFT spectrum, are used to determine a correlation between the recorded data and a watermelon’s sweetness level, which is measured by a refractometer in ˚Brix. After testing numerous watermelons, a linear regression model was developed to predict a watermelon's potential sweetness. Current results are very promising, with the predicted results being within 10% of the measured value. This process is being programmed into an iPhone app so that testing can be done at any location within seconds. The hope is to make the process available to the public in an effort to regularly select better watermelons for consumption before leaving the store and cutting into the watermelon.

column33: Szeto-Schiller (SS)-31 attenuates Doxorubicin induced cardiomyocyte senescence
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
SS-31 attenuates Doxorubicin induced cardiomyocyte senescence. 
Le Nguyen1,2, Jiaojiao Fan1, Lixin Xie1, Gabriela Ramirez1,3, and Huiliang Zhang1 
1. Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology, University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences 
2. Department of Biology, University of Arkansas – Fort Smith  
3. Department of Biology, Henderson State University

Doxorubicin (DOX) is a chemotherapeutic medicine used for the treatment of many types of cancer; however, the use of DOX in clinical practice has been limited because of side effects, notably cardiotoxicity. However, there is no effective treatment for the DOX-induced cardiomyocyte injury. The peptide Szeto-Schiller (SS)-31 (H-D-Arg-Dmt-Lys-Phe-NH2, elamipretide) targets to mitochondria and reduces the reactive oxygen species (ROS) production in the diseased cardiomyocytes. Our preliminary data showed that SS-31 attenuates 50nM DOX induced cardiomyoblast H9C2 cell senescence. To be more translationally, in this study, we further evaluated whether SS-31 ameliorates the DOX induced human induced pluripotent stem cell differentiated cardiomyocytes (hiPSC-CMs) senescence. We differentiated the hiPSCs to cardiomyocytes by RBA protocol and the cells started beating at ~ day 8. Then the hiPSC-CMs were treated with 50 µM DOX for 3 hours and cultured for 48-72 hours. The SS-31 were added with DOX treatment and after removal of the DOX. We tested the senescence markers p16, p21 and MMP3. We found that p21 was increased after DOX treatment for 18 hours and was partially reduced by 1µM SS-31. The expression of p16 and MMP3 was upregulated after 50nM DOX treatment for 18 hours (p16) and 48 hours (MMP3), whereas SS-31 failed to reduce the elevation of p16 and MMP3. This data suggested that SS-31 protects the DOX induced senescence in the hiPSC-CMs. We will further test senescence associated secretory phenotype markers TNFa, IL-6, and IL-1β.

column33: Monitoring Per- and Polyfluoroalkyl Substances in Central Arkansas Surface Water - 2
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) are a man made chemical that does not break down in the environment. PFAS often are found near military bases or manufacturing facilities and can seep into our water supply. They are an emerging public health issue, because of their known toxicity. To our knowledge, there is no data on PFAS in surface water in Arkansas. Thus, we set out to obtain preliminary data on 31 PFAS in Central Arkansas surface waters. Through this research, these 31 PFAS were monitored in Fourche Creek and Rock Creek. Samples were collected in groups of 3 at various locations, and run through solid phase extraction prior to analysis by Liquid Chromatography and Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS). The analysis was based on the EPA 1633 Draft Method. Six of 31 PFAS were detected in samples from Fourche Creek. Four of 31 PFAS were detected in Rock Creek. Future monitoring of PFAS in the water systems will provide essential data for accurate risk assessment and will enable policy makers to make informed decisions.

column33: Computationally Modeling Outputs for Cardiac Fibroblasts  and Networking Signaling Pathways
column43: Cardiac fibroblasts are an essential part of the structural integrity of the heart. These cells regulate the extracellular matrix scaffolding which is critical to the heart's ability to function mechanically, chemically, and electrically. Through focusing on the different ways these cardiac fibroblasts react to certain stimuli, it can be predicted on how to treat the heart when these stimuli disrupt its integrity in various disease conditions. It has been found that the heart has a network of proteins and other small molecules that interact to create a cascade of signaling pathways. The goal of our research is to map out newly discovered pathways related to fibroblast activation protein and show how they interact with the already existing pathways using a computer program called Netflux. Our computational simulations aim to determine how different levels of each small molecule affect the outputs of the pathway. Through this computational research, different levels of each molecule can be entered and determining the outcome of effects of different stimuli can be done electronically instead of needing to be done on physical cells. This virtual therapy screen can greatly accelerate the discovery of novel compounds for improving extracellular matrix structure contributing to heart disease.

column33: Temporal progression of amyloid induced changes of ferritin in the cortex and hippocampus of transgenic Alzheimer disease rat
column43:
Introduction

Excessive deposition of amyloid-beta (Aβ) plaques and neurofibrillary tangles are two salient features of AD. The accumulation of metals in Amyloid Plaques has been suggested to play an important role in the development of Alzheimer’s Pathology. To establish a causative relationship, this study examines the buildup of the protein Ferritin within the Microglia of the brain. Ferritin is an important protein that maintains iron homeostasis by oxidizing the metal into less reactive species. Ferritin has two isoforms, one that is H-rich, and one that is L-rich. Central Nervous system microglia contain L-rich ferritin. 

Purpose


To determine a causative relationship between buildup of iron within Amyloid plaques, and the progression of AD Pathology. 


Methods

Rat brain sections were cut 25 microns thin, and stained with Congo red.  Ferritin was visualized by using light-microscopic histochemistry, and Congo red was used to determine whether deposition of ferritin was related to the buildup of Amyloid plaques. 

Results

In Transgenic rat, ferritin levels increased with time in both the Cortex and anterior hippocampus. In non-transgenic mice, there was no discernable correlation over time. In both male and female 6 months old rat, Ferritin was ubiquitously present in the brain. Most of the cortical and hippocampal ferritin are of microglial type with intense cell body with processes, however, the thalamus, striatum, and amygdala show circular ferritin cells with no apparent processes. In the transgenic AD rat, ferritin in the cortex was seen proliferated around the plaques and hippocampus in both sexes compared to their non-TG counterparts. 

Conclusion

Two way ANOVA tests indicate strong statistical significance for increase in ferritin levels. It is possible to conclude that iron buildup is causative on the progression of AD pathology.

column33: Role of PLPP3 in human stem cell-derived endothelial cell differentiation and function
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Heart disease is the leading cause of deaths in the US, with coronary artery disease (CAD) being the most common cardiovascular disease. Lipid phosphate phosphatases (LPPs) are membrane-bound enzymes that dephosphorylate a broad range of bioactive lipids including lysophosphatidic acid (LPA). Of the three mammalian LPPs, global deletion of the PLPP3 gene encoding LPP3 in mice leads to early embryonic lethality due to defects in blood vessel formation. Adult mice with deletion of PLPP3 in endothelial cells (conditional KO) have increased vascular permeability. PLPP3 variants that result in lower LPP3 protein levels are associated with increased risk of CAD in humans. We therefore hypothesized that LPP3 plays a critical role in endothelial cell (EC) differentiation and function. To investigate this possibility, we used gene editing approaches to disrupt the PLPP3 gene in human induced pluripotent stem cells.  LPP3 protein and mRNA were undetectable in these cells. Wildtype (WT) and PLPP3 null iPSCs were differentiated into mature endothelial cells (iPSC-ECs) using specialized media. OCT4 gene expression, a pluripotent stem cell marker, remained unchanged between the genotypes, validating pluripotency. However, there were marked differences in morphology and growth patterns. WT cells assumed a cobblestone morphology and grew uniformly typical of endothelial cells in vitro, while KO cells grew as clusters in a haphazard manner. PECAM1, a hallmark of endothelial cells responsible for junction integrity, was significantly reduced in the LPP3 KO iPSC-ECs. These findings suggest a reduced differentiation and developmental potential in cells lacking LPP3. Ongoing studies will likely provide evidence of disruption of barrier function in tube-formation assays. Our findings from this project and future studies may provide a mechanistic understanding of the role of LPP3 in vascular development and disease and have broader implications for diseases involving endothelial cells.

column7: National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: Safety assessment of Zileuton nano-crystal drug by evaluating Alanine Aminotransferase using plasma and ileum tissue
column43:
Zileuton is classified as a BCS class II drug, characterized by its low solubility and high permeability. Upon administration, the drug acts as an inhibitor of the enzyme 5-lipoxygenase, thereby impeding the process of leukotriene synthesis which is involved in asthma pathogenesis. Because of the beneficial effect, this drug is frequently prescribed for the treatment of chronic asthma and other inflammatory diseases. However, the long-term administration of zileuton therapy exhibited a correlation with elevated levels of alanine aminotransferase (ALT; originally referred to as serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase (SGPT)), thereby suggesting hepatotoxicity. To mitigate the challenges associated with solubility and bioavailability, our lab has developed a nanocrystal formulation that has demonstrated beneficial outcomes. The primary objective of this study is to examine the effects of the zileuton nanocrystal formulation on the levels of the ALT enzyme in the plasma and ileal tissue and compared to other conventional formulations (physical mixture, pure drug and other excipients used in formulation) as well as positive control. 
	In this study, the rats were subjected to various forms of zileuton treatment for 15 days including active pharmaceutical ingredient, zileuton nanocrystal formulated drug, and physical mixture. In addition to these zileuton-treated groups, other groups were treated with an empty capsule (placebo) or served as control animals that received no treatment. Plasma samples were obtained at three time points: 1 hour, day 8, and day 15. Ileal tissue samples were only collected on day 15. The findings demonstrated a significant statistical difference (p < 0.05) between several of the treatment groups, as observed in both the ileum tissue and the plasma. Additionally, intriguing findings have been observed in the comparison between genders, as well as between the time points of day 8 and day 15.  The findings will be disclosed during the presentation.

column33: The Development of a New Water-Soluble Zinc Porphyrin, ZnTPP-2MP, as a Photodynamic  Therapy Agent
column43: Photodynamic therapy is a new technique used in cancer treatment involving the use of a photosensitizer and light exposure to kill malignant cells. In this research, the use of ZnTPP-2MP as a photosensitizer using red and white light as a source of radiant light energy was explored in examining the cytotoxicity of the new porphyrin as possible treatment of the NIH 3T3 fibroblast cancer cell line. ZnTPP-2MP was synthesized by the reaction of the porphyrin, ZnTPPC, with 2-amino-2-methyl-1-propanol.  Following synthesis, the new porphyrin was purified by column chromatography using Sephadex LH-20 and G-50. Lastly, the efficacy of ZnTPP-2MP as a photosensitizer was examined by analyzing its cytotoxicity when paired with white light and red light using MTT assay on the NIH 3T3 fibroblast cancer cell line.

column33: The mechanism of BAK activation by PUMA in apoptosis initiation
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Mitochondrial apoptosis initiates through mitochondria poration, a process directed by pro-apoptotic BCL-2 family proteins. To induce mitochondrial poration, the pore-forming protein BAK is activated from a dormant state by the BH3-only BCL-2 family proteins including BID, BIM, and PUMA through protein-protein interactions. How PUMA activates BAK remains unresolved, and we sought to investigate this mechanism. A crystal structure of the BH3 domain of PUMA bound to BAK has revealed that binding of the BH3 at the hydrophobic groove of BAK destabilizes the inhibitory helix α1 of BAK, as observed in other BH3 complexes with BAK. Moreover, the AlphaFold structure of the complex of full-length BAK and PUMA has indicated a C-terminal tail following the BH3 domain, which forms a short α-helix possibly implicated in atypical membrane tethering. We tested these structure-based hypotheses in binding and
functional assays using peptide-based PUMA BH3 mutants, truncated PUMA constructs, and a BAK mutant refractory to direct activation by BH3 ligands. To confirm BH3-in-groove binding, in fluorescence polarization groove-binding assays, the wildtype (WT) PUMA BH3 peptide bound
to BAK with similar affinity as the prototypical direct activator WT BID BH3 peptide, both being similarly able to trigger BAK-mediate liposome permeabilization. Compared to the WT PUMA BH3, rationally designed missense PUMA BH3 mutations that exhibited higher or lower affinity
for BAK promoted diminished and enhanced BAK-mediated liposome permeabilization, but none of them triggered the activation-deficient BAK mutant. The contributions of the disordered regions outside of the BH3 are also being investigated mechanistically considering the AlphaFold structure of the complex. Our results support the hit-and-run weak affinity nature of the PUMA BH3–BAK interaction underlying efficient direct BAK activation and membrane poration.

column33: Is It Worth It? Can Taking An Asthma Course Lower Hospitalization Rates For People With Asthma?
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Is It Worth It? Can Taking An Asthma Course Lower Hospitalization Rates For People With Asthma? 
 Jacob Pham, Clare C Brown, Ph.D. MPH2,
College of Public Health, UAMS2

Asthma is a chronic, incurable case that affects millions of Americans. With no cure, people used medication to help to reduce asthma symptoms. However, controller medications are being underused, while reliever medications are overused; Recent studies also have found that asthma education and courses reduce the risk of asthma-related death (Zhang et al., 2021). The current study aims to assess whether patients with asthma who take asthma training courses have lower ED rates than patients who do not. This study used data from the 2019 and 2020 Asthma Call Back Survey (ACBS) of the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) to determine if there is a correlation between taking an asthma course and ED visits and hospitalizations. Outcomes included an ER visit, doctor visit, asthma plan, or asthma course. Statistics included chi-square tests and a logistic regression adjusting for insurance, race, gender, smoking status, if the individual had an asthma plan, city or rural residence, and age. There were 22,934 people unweighted and 39,641,425 weighted from 2019 and 2020. We found that 29.42% had an asthma plan, 12.25% had a hospitalization visit, and 40.07 had an ED visit. People were more likely to go to the ER if they had insurance (1.13), were Native American (2.34), Hispanic (1.18), or Black (1.27), and had at least smoked at some point. If the patient had taken an asthma course, they would likely have an asthma plan (5.71). We found that patients who took an asthma class, had an asthma plan, or had both reported higher ER visits. Patients who smoked were more likely to end up in the ER, and those living in rural areas had fewer ER and ED visits.

column33: Nutrition Assessment of Older Adults Using the Nutrition Focused Physical Examination
column43:
The NFPE is an in-depth examination of a patient from head-to-toe by a trained nutrition professional. It can identify or confirm muscle wasting, subcutaneous fat loss, and edema and clarify information gathered during the medical record review. In the long-term, initial and continual assessment of an individual’s nutritional status and progression toward standard outcomes will result in less complications and better outcomes.
Using height and weight, BMI for each participant was measured. Thirty-three percent (n=8) were males and sixty-seven percent (n=16) were females out of the twenty-four total participants in this study. Each participant was placed in a category of underweight, normal weight, or overweight based on the BMI chart values for senior adults (age 65 or above). A BMI of 23 is considered underweight, 23-30 is normal weight, and above 30 is considered overweight. For males, 25% (n=2) were overweight, 37.5% (n=3) were normal, and 37.5% (n=3) were underweight. Females had a majority in the overweight category with a total of 43.8% (n=7). Twenty-five percent (n=4) were underweight, and 31.3% (n=5) were a normal BMI weight.

column33: Analysis of Cancer Cell Survival Using AI Confluence Analysis
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Pancreatic cancer is a deadly disease leading to 50,550 deaths per year in the USA and ranks as the eighth most common cancer among females and the tenth most common cancer among males. Our laboratory has employed the clonogenic assay to determine the extent of cell death under various conditions for treating pancreatic cancer. However, this assay typically requires a time frame of 10 days to yield reliable outcomes. Recognizing the prolonged duration of the clonogenic assay, our research group aims to explore alternative methods that can provide similar results within a shorter time frame.
To address this, we hypothesized that utilizing the incucyte method would yield comparable results to the conventional clonogenic assay, while significantly reducing the time required. Three pancreatic cancer cell lines, namely Pan-1, MP2, and Bxpc-3, were employed in our study. These cell lines were subjected to diverse conditions, dilutions, and treatments in both 96-well and 6-well format. 
Our investigation yielded a significant finding: the incucyte method proved to be more effective than the traditional clonogenic assay. Remarkably, the results obtained from both methods were highly similar, indicating the potential of the incucyte method as a time-efficient alternative.

column33: Using CRISPR to Inactivate Candidate DNA Repair Genes in Bdelloid Rotifers
column43: Bdelloid rotifers are microscopic invertebrates that reside in freshwater environments. These creatures possess the ability to survive desiccation not by preventing DNA damage, like in many eukaryotes, but instead by repairing DNA damage caused by desiccation. However, the mechanism for this repair is unknown. Identifying candidate genes and proteins that regulate DNA repair is vital to understanding this process. Furthermore, previous work has identified an atypical DNA ligase homolog (bdLIG) in Adineta vaga that is upregulated following DNA damage. The objective of this project was to use CRISPR genome editing to inactivate the bdLIG gene in the bdelloid Adineta vaga to investigate its role in DNA repair. To achieve this, two sgRNAs were designed to excise the bdLIG and GAPDH (as a control) from the genome. In vitro Cas9 cleavage assays were used to determine the efficiency of the sgRNAs. DNA templates were designed to replace the target genes during homology-directed repair. For CRISPR in A. vaga, different electroporation conditions using GFP- tagged Cas9 were explored. Then, CRISPR was carried out by electroporating embryos with the sgRNA/ Cas9 complexes and GFP repair template. For evidence of genome editing, rotifers were examined under a fluorescence microscope for GFP expression. Once a mutant rotifer with the inactivated bdLIG gene is identified, individuals will be desiccated and subsequently rehydrated to induce DNA repair. The recovery rate for desiccated wild-type rotifers at varying time stamps was determined in this project. Thus, a reduced rate of recovery in mutant rotifers compared to the wild-type would insinuate the bdLIG gene plays a crucial role in DNA repair.

column33: Validating qPCR assay to quantify HCoV-NL-63
column43: Being able to detect and quantify a virus during an experiment simply and quickly is important. Currently, the alphacoronavirus NL-63 is proposed to be a safe surrogate for the SARS-CoV-2 virus, which is the etiological agent of COVID-19. A surrogate virus has the same molecular mechanism as a more deadly virus, but produces self-limiting infections. While the pandemic is over, finding suitable surrogates to study viruses safely is essential to help head off future outbreaks. Also, finding ways to increase research in BSL-2 environments using surrogates serves to enhance research speed and efficiency in the future. However, little is known about ways to quickly quantify NL-63. The current gold-standard is immunofluorescence; however, this takes time and requires expensive reagents and equipment to read results. We propose a qPCR assay that is specific and sensitive for the nucleocapsid of NL-63. First, we designed the qPCR primers to the conserved ORF1 region of the NL-63 virus and validated them for specificity. The amplification efficiency of the qPCR assay was determined and consistently performed at 90-110%, with melt curves indicating a lack of non-specific amplifications and dimer formation. Additionally, using cDNA from an experimentally infected animal with NL-63 that was previously quantified, we ran a full doubling dilution curve and ran the amplicons on a 2% agarose gel. Data indicates that using native NL-63, semi-quantitatively, we have excellent amplification through the full range of dilution. The repeatability of the stability of the curve and lack of untargeted amplification indicates that the primers are likely suitable for downstream analyses. Additionally, the qPCR protocol only required four hours compared to two days using immunofluorescence. Further analyses will include evaluating the primers for sensitivity and specificity using quantified RNA standards and evaluating how closely the NL-63 qPCR assay compares to immunofluorescent technique.

column43:
Excessive mitochondrial proton entry induced H9C2 cell senescence.
Gabriela Ramirez1,2, Jiaojiao Fan1, Le Nguyen1,3, Lixin Xie1, and Huiliang Zhang1
1. Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology, University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
2. Department of Biology, Henderson State University 
3. Department of Biology, University of Arkansas - Fort Smith
Contact: hzhang2@uams.edu

Cardiac disease is the leading cause of death in the aged (˃65 years-old) population. However, the mechanism of cardiac aging remains elusive. Mitochondrial proton leak is increased in the aged cardiomyocyte. We hypothesize that the augmented proton leak contributes to cardiac senescence. To test this hypothesis, we evaluated whether the proton ionophore, dinitrophenol (DNP) which carries the proton from inter membrane space to the matrix to mimic the excessive proton leak in the cardio myoblast H9C2 cell line. We found that DNP concentration dependently decreased the cell growth rate. Also, ?? µM DNP induced H9C2 cell senescence with ?? days. These data suggest that the excessive proton leak is a cause of cardiomyocyte senescence. We will further evaluate the DNP induced H9C2 cell senescence with other acceptable markers, such as p16, p21, TNFα, IL-6 and IL1β.

column33: Analysis of BPA Leaching from Feminine Hygiene Products into Simulated Vaginal Fluid using Fluorescence Spectrophotometry
column43: Bisphenol-A (BPA) is a chemical compound commonly used to produce several plastics and epoxy resins. Recently, BPA has also been detected in feminine hygiene products. Because of a structural resemblance to estradiol, BPA can act as an endocrine disruptor, which has linked BPA to several health complications such as cancer development, reduced fertility, and early puberty. In recent summer research at Ouachita Baptist University, it was determined that fluorescence spectrophotometry could be used to monitor BPA leaching over time into a 1:1 methanol/water solvent from panty liners, tampons, and tampon applicators. BPA is a fluorescent compound with excitation and emission wavelengths of 278 nm and 304 nm, respectively. Due to the small amount of BPA leaching from feminine hygiene products and the resulting complex sample matrix, the standard addition method was used to calculate the BPA concentrations obtained from these samples. To further analyze the leaching effects, a simulated vaginal fluid was utilized as the solvent to mimic the pH and proteins of the female vagina. The leaching of BPA from menstrual pads was analyzed over a six-hour time period in both the 1:1 methanol/water and simulated vaginal fluid; the fluorescence emission intensity of each sample was determined using the FS-5 spectrofluorometer from Edinburgh Instruments. Analytical figures of merit: linear range, limit of detection, and limit of quantitation were determined for both the 1:1 methanol/water solvent and simulated vaginal fluid methods.

column33: Microplastic Identification in Rural North Central Arkansas’ Water Sources
column43:
Plastics are becoming increasingly pervasive in our environment in the form of micro- and
nanoparticles. They are found in water, soil, air, food and wildlife and are considered a major
pollutant in our ecosystem (Ivleva 2021). There are primary and secondary microplastics in the
environment. Large plastic structures can deposit primary particles into the environment whereas
secondary particles are usually a result of degrading of plastic structures because of the
environment. Plastics are not prone to quick decomposition and can take up to a few thousand
years to break down. Due to this problem, microplastics are taking a toll on the environment that
needs to be analyzed further in order to find a solution (Lai 2022). Microplastic contamination in
rural Arkansas water systems remains an under-researched area. We collected water samples from
multiple sources in glass vials, and employed multiple analytical methods to identify
the microplastics from each source. In rural areas with minimal human interaction we
expect for there to be less microplastic contamination concentration compared with our more urban
sources with frequent human interaction.

column33: Examining Differences in the Hospitalization Outcomes of Patients with Diabetes Mellitus(DM)
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43:
Diabetes has been taking over many people's lives, we even found that 5% of multi-morbidity patients are responsible for 50% of the US’s spending on healthcare. We also found that 1 in 5 people with diabetes don’t know they have it. People with diabetes commonly have other chronic disorders along with diabetes. The purpose of this study was to examine the extent to which race influenced hospitalization outcomes(i.e., hospitalization, days  between readmission, readmission rates, and length of stay) of multi-morbidity patients with a triad of diabetes, depression, and obesity. Deidentified electronic medical record data from the Arkansas Clinical Data Warehouse were collected on 4,156 patients, representing 189,212 hospital encounters between January 1, 2014 and September 9, 2021. Binomial logistic regression assessed associations between specific hospital outcomes and race, and the Mann Whitney-U assessed racial differences in hospital outcomes.  Native Americans had a statistically significantly higher median difference in hospitalizations rates than the rest of the races(i.e., 21.5)(i.e.,African Americans, Caucasian Americans, Asian Americans, and American Indians).Furthermore, we can also conclude that each race had a statistically similar median  length of stay.  Over the 7-year study period, we found African Americans had a significantly higher median difference in total number of readmission days (i.e., 2475). We see this similar statistic translate over to median differences in total readmissions over the 7-year study period. African Americans also have a statistically higher median difference in total number of readmissions(i.e., 86). Asian Americans and Native Americans had a statistically higher median difference in average time between readmissions (i.e., 37).
Furthermore, we need improved clinical practice for multi-morbidity patients suffering with these problems to reduce the rate at which these patients are being admitted to the hospital.

column33: Investigating the ROCK1 independent regulation of Rnd3’s effects on Lung Adenocarcinoma cell migration
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: With an estimated 2 million diagnoses and 1.8 million deaths globally, lung cancer is one of the most common and deadliest cancer types, with patients experiencing a 5 year survival rate of just ~21%. Many lung cancers metastasize, often contributing to poor prognosis. Rnd3, a RhoGTPase and regulator of many cellular processes that are often dysregulated in cancer, has been observed to have an effect on several cancers through varying expression levels. We observed significantly higher survival rates of lung adenocarcinoma patients with lower expression of Rnd3 following analysis of TCGA survival data. Generation of global protein expression profiles of Rnd3 expressing and Rnd3 knockdown A549 lung adenocarcinoma cells using proteomic analysis and Ingenuity Pathway Analysis of resulting data predicted that low Rnd3 expression would decrease cell invasion and migration, two properties frequently related to metastasis. Validation of these predictions revealed Rnd3 knockdown significantly decreased cell migration and invasion but also that Rnd3 regulation of cell invasion and migration was independent of ROCK1 signaling, indicating a novel pathway. In this study, we knocked down two known interactors of Rnd3 and regulators of cell migration, p190RhoGAP and RhoA, to further investigate the ROCK1-independent regulatory mechanism that Rnd3 utilizes to regulate cell migration. Wound healing assays were used to measure cell migration of A549 cells following knockdown of p190RhoGAP and RhoA individually and with Rnd3 knockdown. These data can be used to identify the role of p190RhoGAP and RhoA in Rnd3 regulation which could potentially assist in identification of additional factors involved in Rnd3’s regulation of cell migration. Identifying the novel pathway in which Rnd3 regulates cell migration could identify therapeutic targets and new treatment strategies for millions of patients suffering from one of the most lethal cancer types.

column33: Detection of BPA in Clothing using Fluorescence Spectrophotometry
column43:
Bisphenol-A (BPA) is a carcinogenic compound found in many plastic-containing products due to its ability to add rigidity and strength to the plastic. However, BPA has been found in a wide variety of products not traditionally thought of as “plastic,” including feminine hygiene products, printer receipts, and even clothing containing a polyester/spandex blend. BPA in clothing indicates possible dermal exposure to BPA—which is traditionally excluded from human BPA exposure analysis—as well as environmental exposure through clothing discarded in landfills.
	BPA is a fluorescent compound, with an excitation wavelength of 278 nm and an emission wavelength of 304 nm. Using fluorescence spectrophotometry, the presence of BPA in polyester/spandex blended clothing was determined by monitoring the leaching of BPA from the fabric over time. Strips of clothing containing polyester/spandex blends were submerged in a 1:1 methanol/water solution for varying amounts of time, ranging from 0 minutes to 6 hours, allowing BPA to seep out of the material. Using the standard addition method to control for other compounds that could also possibly be leaching out of the material, the sample solution (5 mL) and varying amounts of stock solution (0 mL, 2 mL, 5 mL, 7 mL, 10 mL) were added to 25- mL volumetric flasks for each time point and diluted to the line with 1:1 methanol/water solution. The concentration of BPA that leached from the material was then determined by using the Edinburgh Instruments FS-5 to measure the fluorescence emission intensity. Statistical analysis was performed on the results, including linear range, limit of detection, and limit of quantitation.

column33: Investigation into the Role of Rev1 and Interacting Partners in Resolution of G4 Sequences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Translesion DNA synthesis (TLS) is a vital process to bypass replication stress or DNA damage to avoid replication fork stalling, mutations, double-stranded breaks, or cancer. One such stressor is a G-quadruplex (G4), a non-canonical DNA structure frequently encountered in G-rich regions of the genome. G4 structures require specialized proteins for binding and resolution. Rev1, a Y-family polymerase, is heavily involved in this activity, and allows replication to continue unhindered at sites of G4 sequences. We have previously shown using a supF mutagenesis assay with a G4 containing sequence placed in the lagging strand of a pSP189 plasmid that in HAP-1 cells deficient in Rev1, there is a >200-fold greater mutation frequency compared to Rev1-proficient cells (Ketkar et al., 2021). We will now investigate the positional effect on mutation frequency when G4 is placed in the leading strand of the pSP189 plasmid and compare results. Our previous work, using site-directed mutagenesis has shown the important role played by residues E466 and Y470 of human Rev1 in binding and resolving G4 DNA. We will conduct similar mutagenic studies to produce catalytically inactive Rev1 (D570A/E571A) either by itself, or in combination with the insert-2 mutations, to investigate whether catalytic activity of Rev1 is essential for binding and replication of G4. Questions surrounding the mechanism by which Rev1 works, particularly with respect to its recruitment of other proteins to resolve G4 sequences, remain. The C-terminal domain of Rev1 is believed to play a crucial role in protein interactions. Towards this end, a cell line that stably expresses Rev1 with C-terminal deletion (1-1040) will be generated. This cell line will be used in techniques like isolation of proteins on nascent DNA (iPOND), as well as immunofluorescence microscopy approaches like proximity-ligation assays to investigate the role of various Rev1 motifs in protein recruitment at G4 sites.

column33: Design of an Open-Source, 3D-Printable Absorption Spectrometer
column43: Absorption spectroscopy is an analytical technique used to determine the chemical makeup, concentration, or pH of a sample by obtaining an absorption measurement. Spectroscopy concepts are generally covered in undergraduate chemistry courses; however, the high cost of purchasing and maintaining commercial absorption spectrometers restricts access to research-grade instruments. To provide an affordable and functional alternative to commercial absorption spectrometers, we propose an open-source, Arduino-controlled, 3D-printable absorption spectrometer. Assembly includes an Arduino microcontroller, inexpensive electrical and optical hardware, open-source code, and 3D-printable optomechanical components designed using the Fusion 360 CAD program. In this work, we demonstrate that this instrument can detect absorbance spectra and changes in absorbance signal in real time. By comparing the spectra to spectra detected by a commercial absorption spectrometer and by using the instrument to demonstrate a linear relationship between absorbance and concentration, we show that this design offers an affordable way to incorporate absorption spectroscopy into educational and research laboratories.
