column33: Investigating HELB Recruitment Patterns and ATR Influence in DNA Replication Stress
column43: DNA replication stress presents a formidable challenge to cellular integrity. DNA helicase, HELB, plays a pivotal role in facilitating cellular recovery from this stress. While HELB's role in DNA repair is established, its involvement in DNA replication and the precise mechanisms underlying its function and interactions with other proteins remain uncertain and warrant further investigation. ATR is the master kinase regulating the replication stress response, which suggested a potential link between HELB phosphorylation by ATR and its recruitment to sites of single-stranded DNA exposure, where it interacts with replication protein A (RPA). The primary objective of this study was to examine the influence of ATR on HELB recruitment during DNA replication stress. Wild-type cells were treated with hydroxyurea (HU) and HU in conjunction with the ATR inhibitor AZD6738 to induce replication stress and prevent activation of the replication stress response respectively. To establish a control for ATR function, this experiment monitored the phosphorylation status of Chk1, a downstream target of ATR. By evaluating the presence of HELB in the soluble fraction, chromatin fraction, and whole-cell extract under varying treatment conditions, the primary aim was to elucidate HELB recruitment patterns and investigate the interplay between ATR and HELB during the DNA replication stress response. Additionally, GAPDH and histone H4 were employed as controls for the soluble and chromatin fractions, respectively, ensuring the precision of the fractionation techniques employed. With this method, we found that HELB is recruited to chromatin in response to HU treatment in an ATR-independent manner. The forthcoming phase of this study aims to investigate the necessity of replication fork reversal catalysis by SMARCAL1 and ZRANB3 for HELB recruitment. Additionally, we aim to investigate the requirement of HELB's interaction with RPA and/or ATPase activity in its chromatin localization process.

column33: Mechanisms connecting inflammation to astrocytic glucose transport: relevance to Alzheimer’s disease
column43: Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by progressive cognitive decline, memory loss, and neuronal death. A predominance of the evidence indicates that AD is precipitated by accumulation of the amyloid ꞵ-peptide, which elicits an inflammatory response in the brain that includes an elevation in the levels of cytokines such as interleukin-1ꞵ (IL-1ꞵ) and tumor necrosis factor (TNF). Growing research also suggests a relationship between the dysregulation of brain glucose metabolism and the pathology of AD. Astrocytes, the most abundant glial brain cells, are essential for maintaining homeostasis in the brain, especially the conveyance of glucose from blood vessels to neuronal elements deeper in the brain parenchyma. Astrocytes primarily transport glucose through glucose transporter 1 (GLUT1) enzyme. Aꞵ and a combination of IL-1ꞵ and TNF can disrupt GLUT1 regulation, resulting in attenuated glucose transport. Findings in other systems suggest that thioredoxin-interacting protein (TXNIP) or GRP78/BiP may respond to cytokines and influence GLUT1. In primary cultures of astrocytes, TXNIP was manipulated through a molecular approach (RNAi) and GRP78/BiP pharmacologically (small-molecule inhibitor) to test the impact on glucose uptake in the presence and absence of cytokines. Initial results indicate a role for GRP78/BiP but not TXNIP, findings being tested through ongoing experiments. Determining the mechanisms involved in glucose dysregulation in AD may provide therapies relevant to both symptoms and progression of AD.

column33: Maximizing Nature: Using Dihydrocodeine To Fight Leukemia
column43:
Leukemia is a disease of the blood and bone marrow that are composed of active cells and quiescent cells, also known as Leukemia stem cells (LSCs). In Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML), normal and agressive chemotherapy tends to only target active cells but not LSCs, which causes disease relapes and eventully death. There is a 20-year survival rate of 7% and %-year survival rate of 26%. Improved and new chemotherapy that targets active and stem cells of Leukemia are needed. This project aims to look at small compounds that are able to permeate and destroy Leukemia cells. We also aim to manipulate Dihydrocodeine (DHL) chemistry structure and chemistry in order to increase drugability. We will puposliy focus on the compound's ability to bind to Leukemia cells, potency in LSCs, and the anti-Leukemia posibilities. We will use structure based design to synthasize the compound. We will then compare it effectiveness on killing Leukemia cells. By minpulating cell structure and permeability of DHL, we aim to kill Leukemia and reduce desease relapse. 
Keywords: Dihydrocodeine, DHL, sythasize, compound, Leukemia, binding, cell structure, chemistry, anti-leukemia

column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Despite the improved and updated treatments available currently, breast cancer is the most prominent and common type of cancer among women. Unfortunately, most of the common chemotherapeutics used in the treatment of breast cancer develop cognitive impairments, or chemobrain, which may affect the quality of life in the survivors. Cyclophosphamide Methotrexate 5-fluorouracil (CMF), a toxic combination therapy for breast cancer treatment, has significantly increased survival rates in the patients. Recent studies have shown that chemotherapeutics may induce long term cognitive dysfunctions including memory impairment, anxiety, and depression. However, very few studies have shown the underlying mechanisms involved in chemobrain. Hence, the aim of the current study is to assess the mechanisms of prolonged anxiety and depressive behaviors caused by chemotherapeutics in mice. 12 weeks C57/B6 mice were treated with intraperitoneal (IP) injections weekly for 4 weeks of either saline (0.9% NaCl) or CMF (60, 4, and 60 mg/kg, respectively). Force Swim Test (FST), Elevated Plus (EV), Y-Maze, Novel Object Recognition (NOR), and Tail Suspension tests were performed to study anxiety and despair-like behavioral changes. Tandem mass tag (TMT) proteomics will be used to assess neural protein networks in the amygdala along with western blotting to observe neuronal activity and microglial activation. In addition, real-time polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) will be conducted to assess the gene expressions of presynaptic and postsynaptic markers present in the amygdala. Results will be collected and analyzed for discussions and conclusions.

column33: Brittle Breath: Characterization of the Lung Defects in Mouse Models of Osteogenesis Imperfecta
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Osteogenesis Imperfecta (OI) is a rare congenital disease that causes low bone mass and frequent bone fractures. The most common genetic type is caused by dominant mutations in the genes encoding type I collagen. The leading cause of death among OI patients is respiratory disease and complications, and recent research has revealed that there may be primary lung defects responsible for these complications. The hypothesis is that abnormal type I collagen causes primary changes in lung development and composition as it affects the lung's extracellular matrix, which is crucial to lung development, homeostasis, and injury-repair. This project aims to characterize the lung and respiratory phenotype of mouse models of OI using the CrtapKO mouse and a novel Col1a1Floxed/+; EIIa-Cre mouse. Past Histological studies observed morphological differences between these CrtapKO mice and control wild-type mice including alveolar simplification and increased alveolar space. These studies on Col1a1Floxed/+; EIIa-Cre mice are expected to yield similar results. Additionally, a protocol for complete lung dissociation into single-cell suspension for single-cell RNA sequencing of the lung was optimized. This will enable study of the transcriptome changes in these mice. The protocol for single-cell RNA sequencing will require close coordination of lung dissociation, flow cytometry to sort out cells of interest, and finally, sequencing at the UAMS Genomics Core. Flow cytometry was used to eliminate hematopoietic cells (CD45+) and endothelial cells (CD31+) in order to enrich for the cells of interest: fibroblasts and alveolar epithelial cells. Single-cell RNA sequencing is currently scheduled in the second half of July and is expected to reveal a reduction in transcripts involving cell adhesion and movement which would suggest abnormal formation of secondary septae during the alveolar stage of lung development.

column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column14: IDeA National Resource for Quantitative Proteomics Internship Program
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Plate-Based SP4 and Other Plate-Based Sample Preparation Methods for Proteomic Analysis
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Quantitative mass spectroscopy based proteomics is a prominent, modern method for analyzing the proteome of samples. The sample preparation methods within this field are required in order to take a tissue sample and extract the peptides to be loaded into the mass spectrometer. These sample preparation methods require constant innovation to improve efficiency and results. Plate-based sample prep methods are preferred due to their ease, speed, and most predominately, their reproducibility. In this experiment, four different plate-based sample prep methods were compared against a non-plate- based chloroform-methanol extraction. These methods included a plate-based SP4 method, a plate-based SP4 method bypassing the intermediate plate, and a plate-based SP4 method without the use of beads. In addition to this, two different lysis buffers (RIPA and SDS) were used in each method to determine if both are compatible with the methods used.

column7: Ouachita Baptist University
column33: The Genetic Diversity of Warea amplexifolia
column43: Warea amplexifolia is a federally and state endangered plant due to habitat loss and fragmentation that is endemic to the central ridge system of Florida. To aid in recovery of this species, we seek to study if populations of Warea amplexifolia have lost genetic diversity, if certain populations are more diverse than others, and what populations would be best for reintroduction purposes. Whole genomic DNA from Warea amplexifolia was extracted and species-specific primers of ten microsatellite loci were used to amplify and genotype 164 individuals from seven different populations. Initial results indicate that some populations have lower genetic diversity, higher selfing rates, and likely a higher extinction risk than other populations. The populations with the largest number of plants also have the most genetic diversity and thus might be useful as sources for translocation and reintroduction purposes. We will discuss the implications of our research for the management of this critically endangered plant.

column7: National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: “Mechanistic study of imatinib-caused cytotoxicity in hepatic cells”
column43: Imatinib is a tyrosine-kinase inhibitor (TKI) used to treat certain types of leukemias, gastrointestinal stromal tumors, dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans, and system mastocytosis. The use of imatinib in therapeutic settings has been associated with severe hepatic injury; however, the underlying mechanisms are not fully understood. In this study, we investigated the cytotoxicity of imatinib and explored the molecular mechanisms underlying its hepatotoxicity using biochemical and molecular analyses. We found that imatinib decreased ATP content in human primary hepatocytes and HepG2 cells. Imatinib also caused decreased cell viability, increased LDH release, and increased caspase 3/7 activation, indicating the induction of apoptosis and necrosis by imatinib. Furthermore, we examined changes in markers of the apoptosis and endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress pathways using Western blot analysis. In HepG2 cells, treatment with imatinib resulted in increased levels of apoptosis pathway hallmarks, such as PARP cleavage and γH2A.X, while expression levels of ER stress markers, CHOP and XBP-1s did not change.  Moreover, we investigated the role of cytochrome P450s (CYPs) in the metabolism of imatinib using HepG2 cell lines individually expressing 14 CYPs (1A1, 1A2, 1B1, 2A6, 2B6, 2C8, 2C9, 2C18, 2C19, 2D6, 2E1, 3A4, 3A5, and 3A7), as established in our previous work. Using mass spectrometry analyses, we determined that CYP2C8 and 3A4 are responsible for the metabolism of imatinib to N-desmethyl imatinib. In our future studies, we will investigate the potential role of CYP2C8 and 3A4 in the cytotoxicity of imatinib by analyzing whether the cytotoxicity of imatinib can be altered in HepG2 cells overexpressing CYP2C8 or 3A4, compared to the control HepG2 cells.

column7: National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: Assessment of Alternative Skin Barrier Models to Predict Caffeine Dermal Absorption
column43: Skin permeation assessments are an important component of the safety evaluations of cosmetic ingredients and topical drugs, as they inform on the potential for local and systemic exposures. Although excised human skin (EHS) is the ‘gold standard’ for in vitro permeation testing (IVPT) studies, the inherent cost and limited supply of EHS hinders their use in dermal absorption studies. In addition, current IVPT methods have limited throughput, which can be restrictive when performing early dermatological product safety screenings. Here, we developed a 96-well format reconstructed human epidermis (RhE) model, consisting of human neonatal epidermal keratinocytes cultured at the air-liquid interface on permeable support membranes. The in-house RhE model, EHS, and a commercially available RhE model (MelanoDerm, MatTek, Ashland, MA) were tested in parallel for their potential to predict the percutaneous absorption of caffeine in vitro. Caffeine was selected as the test compound because it is a reference hydrophilic compound for IVPT as per OECD guidelines. The barrier function of the three skin barrier models was also evaluated by histology and by measuring their transepidermal water loss (TEWL). Overall, the side-by-side evaluation of several skin models with various methodologies contributes to a better understanding of the potential and limitations of each model to predict human exposure to topical chemicals.

column7: University of Central Arkansas
column33: Synthesis of Copper Complexes Supported by A Binucleating Amide Ligand and Investigation of Their CO2 Reactivity
column43: The goal of our work is to develop new copper complexes with potential application on carbon dioxide conversion. A binucleating amide ligand was employed in order to construct binuclear copper complexes with side-open topology. A group of Cu(II) and Cu(I) complexes have been synthesized and characterized by X-ray crystallography, UV-vis and FT–IR. The diverse structural features of these complexes clearly demonstrated the flexibility of the ligand platform. The Cu(I) complexes showed interesting reactivity towards CO2. Currently our main focus is the characterization of reaction products by GC-MS, IR and NMR.

column7: University of Central Arkansas
column33: Microwave Synthesis of 1-(2-pyridinyl)-1H-benzimidazole for CO2 Reduction
column43: Over time the use of fossil fuels as an energy source has increased and with it the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere has increased as well. This research aims to create an electrocatalyst that will reduce carbon dioxide to carbon monoxide, making for a well-suited pre-catalyst for fuel sources such as methanol and ethanol. To do this, we are making the ligand Bim-py (1-(2-pyridinyl)-1H-benzimidazole). Using 2-bromopyridine, potassium carbonate, and an excess of benzimidazole with a solvent, the Bim-py is made through microwave synthesis. By using a microwave, ligand synthesis can take place in 5-10 minutes, with an additional hour of isolating the product, making it a quickly repeatable process. The currently reported methods require using a Schlenk line and refluxing, which takes up to two days rather than the 1.5 hours with the microwave. Using thin-layer chromatography and 1H NMR, the desired product of Bim-py has been confirmed to be made with results as high as a 71% yield. After making the ligand, it is methylated into [Mebim-py]I. This compound will ultimately be the ligand used to create the catalyst Mn(Mebim-py)(CO)3Br to be tested for efficiency at reducing carbon dioxide.

column7: Lyon College

column5: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: Role of Long-Term consumption of High Fat and High Sucrose Diet on the Microbial Abundance and Diversity in the Genetic Diverse Animal Population
column43:
Role of intestinal microbiome in the development and progression of the extraintestinal diseases has gained interest in many metabolic diseases. Typical American Diet (high fat high sucrose diet; HF/HS diet) is known to play a significant role in the development of Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD) , a metabolic disease that shows interindividual variability in severity. However, the cause of this variability is poorly characterized.  In a previous study (conducted at NCTR), wider range of genetic diverse Cross Collaborative mice (large panel of recombinant inbred mice designed to mirror genetic variability of the human population; CC mice), revealed strain (CC042 and CC011) and sex specific differences in the development of liver pathologies when fed HF/HS for 16 weeks. As host genetics is known to shape the composition of the gut microbiome; the hypothesis of the present study is that a long-term consumption of the HF/HS diet may change the microbial abundance and diversity in CC042 and CC011. We assessed microbial abundance and diversity in the banked samples to dissect the role of long-term consumption (20, 40 and 60 weeks) of HF/HS diet in male and female CC042 and CC011 mice.  Fecal DNA was extracted using the ZYMO Research Fecal Nucleic Acids extraction kit. Intestinal-mucosal DNA was extracted using phenol;/chloroform/isopropanol. Extracted DNA was used to run real time PCR using specific primers for selected bacterial phyla, genus and species. CC011 strain HF/HS diet female and male were moribund before week 20 and 40, respectively. Time-depended effect of HF/HS diet on all survived animals is currently ongoing. 
This study will potentially aide in determining non-invasive methods (such as microbial population distribution as a biomarker in fecal sample) for predicting the population that is predisposed to adverse effects due to HF/HS diet.

column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Correlation between chronic illnesses and low income
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Chronic illnesses are taking over the United States, especially people who come from or are currently in low income households. Hypertension and Obesity are two very common chronic illnesses. Around 2 out of every 3 adult Americans are overweight, while around 1 out of every 3 Americans are Obese. Around 53% of U.S adults have hypertension.  The objective of this study is to prove that people who come from low income households are more prone to chronic illnesses such as hypertension and obesity.  With this information there could be programs or grants set in place to help prevent this from happening further. If the study is proven correct, eventually there could be a program or grant put in place to build a market in a low income neighborhood, to provide access to fresh ingredients. Data from hospital patients at UAMS from the time of 2015 to 2022 was cleaned in the database of open refined. Then, the data was reduced down to better look at each patient. Then the results will be calculated in SPSS statistics. As of right now there is still data being collected and conclusions being made so there are no results at the moment. Through this study and collection of data it will reveal the relationship between low income and chronic illnesses such as hypertension and obesity. This could help to stop food deserts and increase the number of healthy food options in low income communities in the future.

column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Role of Toll-Like Receptor 8 in Foam Cell Dysfunction and Atherosclerosis
column35: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column37: Aiiryel K. McCoy, Andrew Igbokidi, Ryan M. Allen
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD) is the leading cause of death worldwide. ASCVD begins with the accumulation of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) in the vascular wall, where macrophages become engorged with these lipid-rich particles imparting a ‘foamy’ appearance. Foam cells define atherosclerotic lesions, which can naturally resolve, but often progress to complex atherosclerotic plaques of immune infiltrates, ectopic cholesterol, collagen fibers, and necrotic foam cells. Unstable plaques can rupture, generating thrombi that can cause heart attack or stroke. Reducing LDL is a primary intervention for ASCVD; however, gaps in understanding of LDL’s role in foam cell dysfunction present barriers to pharmacological innovation. Recent work has demonstrated that LDL transports small RNAs that activate toll-like receptor 8 (TLR8), a sensor of small RNA that mediates macrophage anti-viral responses. Here, we sought to examine the contribution of TLR8 to foam cell dysfunction. We developed two main objectives, (1) identify novel TLR8 interacting proteins and (2) determine whether TLR8 signals through the molecular target of rapamycin complex (mTORC). For the first objective, we have developed a proximity ligation strategy in which a split biotin ligase is fused to the cytosolic terminus of TLR8. Targeted proximity ligation near early (Rab5) or late (Rab7) endosomes will be validated, and LDL-stimulated TLR8-interacting proteins will be identified by mass spectrometry. For the second objective, we have used luciferase-based reporter assays to assess whether TLR8 activation alters cap-dependent translation, a key component of the mTORC pathway. Preliminary data indicates that LDL and TLR8 augment mTORC activity indirectly through the tumor suppressor protein p53, a key effector of necrotic cell death. Ongoing studies will define this relationship in macrophages in vitro and atherosclerotic plaques in vivo.

column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column14: IDeA Network of Biomedical Research Excellence (INBRE)
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Monitoring Per- and Polyfluoroalkyl Substances in Central Arkansas Surface Water – 1
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Per- and Polyfluoroalkyl Substances (PFAS) are a chemical class of very stable, long-lasting compounds. They are ubiquitous in the environment due to widespread use in industrial and consumer products. PFAS recently attracted public attention across the United States when studies showed an association of PFAS with adverse health effects. As of 2023, there is little to no monitoring or regulation of PFAS in Arkansas. The purpose of this study is to provide preliminary data on PFAS levels in surface water in central Arkansas. Therefore, we set up Liquid Chromatography-Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS) to monitor 31 PFAS using EPA Draft Method 1633. In addition, we obtained 20 authentic PFAS standards to allow accurate quantitation. Samples were collected at various locations along the Saline River and Fourche Creek. Six of 31 PFAS were detected in Fourche Creek. Four of 31 PFAS were detected in the Saline River. Future monitoring of PFAS in the water systems will provide essential data for accurate risk assessment and will enable policy makers to make informed decisions.

column7: Ouachita Baptist University
column33: Characterization of temperate bacteriophage infection of Gordonia species utilizing an optical density-based approach
column43: Bacteriophages are viruses that infect and replicate within bacterial hosts; phage-host interactions, including successful infections, play a role in shaping bacterial populations.  This research aims to describe bacteriophage infection in Gordonia, a soil actinomycete. The infection efficacy of a phage is determined by analyzing the growth of infected bacteria and comparing it to an uninfected host. Optical density measurements are used to describe bacterial growth, with virus infection metrics determined by analyzing optical density values of uninfected and infected cultures over time. These experiments evaluated temperate Gordonia phages Goib, GrandSlam, and Ruthy on host species Gordonia terrae CAG3, Gordonia lacunae, and Gordonia rubripertincta.  Preliminary results confirm findings previously observed in phage lambda, that temperate phages “choose” lysogeny over lysis at a high multiplicity of infection. This research will provide insights into how phage infection dynamics vary among different Gordonia host species, contributing to the understanding of phage-host interactions. The outcomes have implications for fields such as microbial ecology and phage biology, furthering our knowledge of phage infection dynamics and bacteriophage-host interactions.

column5: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: The Associations Between Physical Fitness Activity and Objective Measurements of Sleep in Children
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Sleep plays a crucial role in promoting children’s overall health and well-being. In adults, physical activity improves sleep duration. Nevertheless, a complete understanding of the relationship between physical activity (PA) and sleep in children remains elusive. This study aims to measure the association between physical fitness [PA, aerobic capacity (VO2peak), BMI percentile] and objective measurements of sleep-in children ages 8 to 10 y/o. Children (n=150) attended one study visit. Height and weight were measured, and BMI percentiles were computed using the CDC growth charts. Waist-worn accelerometers (GT9X, Actigraph) were used to measure PA [i.e., moderate to vigorous physical activity (MVPA), and total activity count (AC)] and sleep [ i.e., total sleep time (TST, minutes), wake after sleep onset (WASO), sleep efficiency (SE)]. VO2peak was measured using gas exchange during an incremental cycle ergometer test. The Pearson correlation coefficient was used to assess the relationship between measurements of sleep and physical fitness.

column7: University of Arkansas - Fayetteville
column14: IDeA Network of Biomedical Research Excellence (INBRE)
column33: Label Free Tracking of Cellular Metabolism in Glioblastoma Using Optical Metabolic Imaging in Response to Combined Chemo-Radiotherapy
column43: Glioma constitutes approximately 80% to 85% of malignant brain tumors in adults. Glioblastoma is a type of glioma and the most aggressive form of cancer that originates from the brain. The common subtypes of glioblastoma are glioblastoma IDH wild type (wt) and IDH-mutated astrocytoma (mut), both of which come under grade IV tumors. Optical metabolic imaging technique like multiphoton microscopy (MPM) allows non-invasive, label-free, and quantitative tracking of events happening during cellular metabolism. Two-photon excited fluorescence (TPEF) from intrinsic fluorophores provides physiological and pathological information from biological tissues. Reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) are two endogenous fluorescent coenzymes whose autofluorescence imaging, as well as fluorescence lifetime imaging (FLIM) records changes during metabolism depending on their distributions and concentrations. Precisely, the optical reduction-oxidation (redox) ratio (ORR) of FAD/(FAD + NADH) provides a validated method to quantify the redox state of a cell.  Recent studies from our group have employed ORR to determine the relationship between cellular metabolism and metastatic potential in cancer cells for detecting response to radiation. Radiation therapy and chemotherapy are the two frontline treatment methods following surgery for glioblastoma. Radiation therapy is usually effective when combined with chemotherapy. The primary aim of this project is to evaluate the changes in cellular metabolism in glioblastoma IDH wild type and mutant cell line models in response to radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or combined radiation and chemotherapy. Temozolomide will be used as the chemotherapy drug.

column7: University of Arkansas - Little Rock
column33: The Effects of Sleep Deprivation on Problem Solving with Artificially Induced Schooling: The Inclination of Socialization Over Hunger in Wild Type D. Rerio
column43: Sleep deprivation has been proven to have a negative impact on physical health, mental well-being, and socialization. Sleep deprivation is inducible in animals and is indiscriminate of age or sex. In our research, using the zebrafish model, we investigated the effects of sleep deprivation on decision-making and behavior in the presence of artificially induced schooling, using mirrors, in a complex maze. The goal of this research is to determine whether zebrafish are more inclined to give into innate socialization or if the driving force behind hunger is stronger, in addition, how are these results affected by sleep deprivation? Population sex composition was also altered in addition to the control and sleep-deprived conditions. Composition variations included both control and experimental groups of male-only, female-only, 50% male to female, female minority, and male minority populations. Testing of each group occurred over a five-day period, the first three days of initial testing were used to train and condition the fish to a consistent target area, and in the final two days mirrors were implemented and observations were recorded. Zebrafish are commonly known to be social animals and display schooling behavior. Zebrafish models have also been used to study learning and memory, therefore creating this artificial population would be used to cause a deterrence between the fish and the learned target area. All groups were able to successfully maneuver through obstructions and reach the target area, however, the amount of time taken to reach the target area increased; and interaction time with mirrors, schooling, and behavioral patterns varied between each group. Our findings suggest that sleep deprivation has an impact on socialization and decision-making, and a noticeable regression in the time it took to reach the target area was observed in all groups after the implementation of artificial schooling.

column7: University of Arkansas - Fayetteville
University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)

column24: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Localizing Dietary Effects on Infant Brain Development: A Weakly-Supervised CNN Approach
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Diet is increasingly considered to be an essential environmental factor for early neurodevelopment which is driven by progressive (myelination, synaptogenesis, and neuronal migration) and regressive (synaptic pruning and apoptosis) processes that are heavily influenced by diet-derived growth factors. While breast milk is generally regarded as the optimal nutritional source for infants, little is known about how different infant diets affect brain maturation and development. Inspired by the recent work in computer vision, we introduce a model with class activation mapping technique to localize brain regions and frequency bands during classification of dietary groups. We apply transfer learning to leverage pre-trained AlexNet and GoogleLeNet to extract features from EEG topologies of infants and young children aged 2 months to 6 years that were exclusively fed human milk, dairy-based formula, or soy-based formula for the first 4 months of life. Additionally, the model integrates sex and age as covariates. We will visualize and compare the identified regions and frequency bands with existing findings to determine their potential relevance. We hypothesize that our model will be able to accurately classify the infants into their respective dietary groups, however, the accuracy will diminish throughout early childhood as other environmental influences are introduced.  This research will ultimately inform whether early diet has a persistent effect on functional neurodevelopment throughout infancy and early childhood by illuminating differences in the EEG topologies through our classification model.

column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: Delineating a role for macrophage VEGFR-1 and VEGFR-2 during self-healing cutaneous leishmaniasis
column38: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column41: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column43: Cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL) is a neglected tropical disease that affects an estimated 1.7 million individuals annually. This complex disease is characterized by the interaction between the obligate intracellular parasite, Leishmania spp., and the host’s immune system which can lead to healing or non-healing skin lesions. Our lab has previously shown vascular endothelial growth factor-A (VEGF-A)/vascular endothelial growth factor receptor-2 (VEGFR-2) signaling mediates lymphangiogenesis during L. major infection leading to lesion resolution. VEGF-A is predominantly produced by macrophages and is known to interact with VEGFR-1 and VEGFR-2 receptors on the surface of macrophages, however the role of macrophage VEGFR signaling during L. major infection is unknown. Preliminary work demonstrated that mice deficient for macrophage VEGFR-1 signaling had higher parasitic burdens during L. major infection compared to control mice; additionally, mice deficient for myeloid VEGFR-2 signaling exhibited lower parasite burden compared to control mice. Thus, the goal of this study is to determine the role of VEGF receptors on macrophages during L. major infection in vitro. Cytospin was used on bone marrow derived macrophages to observe parasite growth and parasite killing, through comparisons of untreated infected macrophages and LPS/IFN-γ treated infected macrophages, respectively. In addition, ELISAs were used to observe the expression of TNF- α, a major regulator of inflammation, within macrophage culture supernatants.

column7: National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: Determination of bacteriophage inhibitory abilities toward toxic shock syndrome causing Staphylococcus aureus
column43: As methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus is an ever-increasing obstacle for hospitals and healthcare workers, innovative approaches to the prevention of infection are becoming increasingly relevant within the scientific community.  Prior to the discovery and widespread use of antibiotics, bacteriophages were used to treat infections because of their specificity and replication abilities.  Once antibiotics became accepted as the standard approach to treat bacterial infections, bacteriophage-based treatments diminished in relevance; however, with the increasing difficulty to treat bacterial infections with antibiotics, a renewed interest has occurred in bacteriophage-based treatments.  While bacteriophages are typically used to combat existing infections, this study seeks to utilize bacteriophages to prevent infection.  In an effort to develop a product to prevent the onset of menstrual toxic shock syndrome caused by Staphylococcus aureus, we developed a cocktail containing two bacteriophages proven to inhibit the growth of S. aureus.  In order to find the most promising bacteriophage, 37 clinical S. aureus strains isolated from patients with TSS were examined for the presence of bacteriophages and their ability of those bacteriophages to be bactericidal on TSS-causing strains of S. aureus.  Bacteriophages, isolated from S. aureus strains NCH252 and NCH474, were identified with an ability to plaque, or create zones of clearing, on 85% percent of tested strains.  The purpose of the current study was to assess whether or not bacteriophages can be used prophylactically to prevent the growth of TSS-causing strains of S. aureus when administered in impregnated tampons.  Bacteriophage suspensions from S. aureus strains, NCH252 and NCH474, were lyophilized into commercially available tampons and used in an in vitro syringe model mimicking the vaginal tract containing S. aureus suspended in a modified genital tract secretion medium.

column7: Harding University
column33: Determination of the Viability and Ascorbic Acid Content of Plants Grown in Martian Regolith
column43: As NASA continues its plans to send men to Mars in the near future, there are still many aspects of the journey that remain left to be studied.  One such example is how astronauts will be able to self-sustain on the long journey in space as well as when they finally reach their destination on the planet’s surface, including a source of food that will provide the nutrients needed to remain healthy.  The intent of this project is to find crop options which would produce good sources of nutrients for the astronauts that plan to inhabit the surface of Mars.  Current research includes determining which plants are capable of germinating and growing in Martian regolith soil as well as focusing on plants that are high in essential nutrients, specifically Vitamin C (ascorbic acid).  Differences in growth rates between potting soil and Martian soil were evaluated.  In addition, plants known to contain high amounts of Vitamin C were analyzed for their viability for growing in Martian regolith, as well as evaluating the concentrations of the Vitamin C produced in these plants.

column7: Harding University
University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column14: IDeA National Resource for Quantitative Proteomics Internship Program
column19: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences
column33: HCl Extraction and Propionyl Labeling: Innovation of Histone Extraction for Mass Spectrometry Analysis
column43: Histones are a protein family in which post translational modifications (PTMs) are critical for proper protein function by regulating DNA transcriptional activity. Studying histone PTMs has historically been difficult; however, protein mass spectrometry is capable of analyzing PTMs at low abundance, providing insight into the current state of the system accomplished through mass spectroscopy (MS) to analyze peptide sequences which can then be used to identify proteins. Digestion enzymes are required for conversion of proteins into peptides with trypsin being the most commonly used as it will cleave at every lysine and arginine residue. Traditionally, histone analysis by mass spectrometry has been limited, namely because of challenging protein isolation, the high lysine content, and a lack of capability in identifying PTMs. To combat these problems, we are proposing an acid extraction which isolates basic proteins, including histones. A propionyl anhydride derivatization which adds a propionyl group to every amino group thus preventing trypsin from cleaving at lysine residues. Additionally, a combination of data analysis software will be utilized to identify the specific modifications on the histones. This workflow will enable a proteomic exploration of histone PTMs and delve into epigenetic questions.

column5: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
column7: University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences (UAMS)
National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
National Center for Toxicological Research (NCTR)
column33: Evaluation of sampling volume for the detection of Burkholderia cepacia complex in drinking water
column43: Burkholderia cepacia complex, also known as BCC is an opportunistic pathogen commonly found in water base environment. BCC has been documented as a likely source of contamination in the pharmaceutical manufacturing systems, notably in nonsterile aqueous finish products and water distribution production systems, which has led to numerous recalls of pharmaceutical products. Therefore, developing accurate and reliable methods for BCC detection is crucial in ensuring the quality and safety of pharmaceuticals products. In this study, we are evaluating different sampling volumes to recover and enrich BCC from distilled water, tap water, ground water, and antiseptics solutions (10 μg/ml chlorhexidine dihydrochloride, and 50 μg/ml benzalkonium chloride). Burkholderia cenocepacia AU1054 was serially diluted, and inoculation volumes of 10, 20, 100, and 200 mL were used to target detection of 100, 10, and 1 colony-forming unit (CFU)/L. The samples were cultured at 30 °C for 48 hours in 1/10 TSB and turbidity, as a measure of positive/negative growth, was assessed using optical density (OD600 nm). The results were then confirmed by quantitative polymerase chain reaction (qPCR) using BCC specific primer. Preliminary findings show that the target organism can be recovered at least 90% using 10 mL inoculation volume from 100 CFU/mL, whereas less than 30% recovery rate was observed in 10 CFU/L samples. In contrast, when 100 mL inoculation volume was used, more than 50% recovery rate can be observed in 10 CFU/mL samples. Moreover, a 200 mL sample volume can invariably lead to the detection of as low as 1 CFU/L, regardless of the nature of the water source. These results highlight the importance of collecting adequate volumes of samples using the traditional culture method for more sensitive detection of BCC.
